[White "1. Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ I am very excited to introduce the reader to one of the most complex and popular openings in chess, the Sicilian Defense. Played by every top Grand Master and the greatest talents that chess ever witnessed such as Bobby Fischer and Garry Kasparov. I, Alexandru Banzea from Romania, have been a Fide Master since 2015 and an International Master since the early part of 2020.   My most notable results are the Gold Medal at the European Championship U18 with the Romanian Team where I was playing on the second board in Bad Blankenburg @@StartBracket@@2018@@EndBracket@@, and the Bronze Medal at the Individual Rapid Championship U18 in Oradea 2018. The year 2018 was very special for me because I also managed to win the Romanian Championship U18 in Classical, Rapid and Blitz time controls. When I became a Fide Master in 2015 at the age of 15, I started working with Constantin Lupulescu, one of the biggest experts of the Sicilian in the world, using it to defeat players such as Anish Giri, and Fabiano Caruana.    Engines. I was born in the strong engines era, where having a deep preparation and understanding of the openings is more important than ever. I was 10 years old when I first used an engine, and I remember that Stockfish was gaining a lot of popularity back then, while engines such as IvanHoe and Rybka where around as well. I never really used the Fritz engine, although I think it was not inferior to others at that time.   The game changer came in 2018, when Google introduced its AlphaZero @@StartBracket@@A0@@EndBracket@@, which demolished the top program Stockfish 8 with considerable ease. A0 uses a neural network to play the game of chess, which was a novelty in the world of chess engines. An open-source project, based on Google’s technique, started soon after, and nowadays Leela Zero @@StartBracket@@Lc0@@EndBracket@@ can be used by any chess fan across the globe.  Although Lc0 has a very fine strategical understanding, Stockfish is much more precise when it comes to brute calculation, therefore the perfect combo is to use both when analyzing – just as I did for this course!      My experience in the Sicilian.  I've been an 1.e4 player with the White pieces since forever, while also having 1...c5 as my main weapon against 1.e4 since I was 12. Bobby Fischer is my chess hero, whose repertoire I copied playing his Najdorf, King's Indian, and 1.e4. With more than 8 years of playing the Sicilian Defense with both colors in competitive games, I've developed a good feeling for the positions and for the Opening trends.    The process. I've been working on the lines for more than 500 hours, and have crafted them in the best possible version to make them easy to learn and not get overwhelmed with the big amount of moves there are.   I covered all the important sidelines such as theO'Kelly Sicilian, theNimzowitsch Variation plus the main moves.   Against  2...Nc6  it was easy to go for theRossolimo since it's objectively considered to be the best opening, highly debated in World Championship Matches such the Carlsen-Caruana match in London 2018, or Anand-Gelfand in Moscow 2012.    Against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/3p4/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq -@@EndFEN@@  2…d6 I decided to avoid the crazy amount of theory that can occur in the Najdorf Sicilian and I recommend you to go for the Hungarian Variation, taking with the Queen on d4! This line has always been there and White can play it in more than one way, which is the nice part about it. I recommend you to go for theHarikrishna Variation, which is the set-up based on Qe3-Be2-O-O-h3-Rd1 where White gets an annoying initiative by playing this set-up against basically whatever Black does.    As a kid I struggled to play against the Paulsen Sicilian, but later found out that we can direct the game our way and go for 3.b3! – theWesterinen Attack. I think this line is the most underrated line from the course, having a lot of attacking potential based on the Novelties and Fresh ideas that I have found and included.   How to work with this course.  The point of this course is to give you a general understanding of the Sicilian. With Black having so many ways to reply, I decided to recommend setups that are easy to learn, that focus on plans and do not rely on move-by-move theory. I recommend that you to have a look at all the lines; I know that you may face the sidelines rarely, but even when you do, having a general idea of what is what will help you tremendously. Going through all the details as well is going to improve your chess understanding considerably due to the variety of positions, and the multitude of ideas that you can learn! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Quickstarter"]
[Black "O'Kelly Sicilian "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 a6
{ The O'Kelly Sicilian has arrived on the board! This is a very tricky variation for White because the Open Sicilian is not working well here as you can see in the upcoming notes.   I used this line myself when I started chess about 10 years ago with very decent results against club players – nobody knew how to react against it! Back then it was considered to be a somewhat dubious line for Black and it was rarely seen in Grandmaster games.   Nowadays, this line has become very popular even at the 2600+ level mainly because of Vladislav Artemiev playing it in more than 20 games.   Why has this line become more and more popular? Well, I would say that the fact that you play the Sicilian as Black,and White can't go for the Open Sicilian is pretty powerful. Back in the days people had a superficial opinion about this variation because it was considered that after either 3.c4 or 3.c3 White gets a free advantage. As theory has advanced, I invite you to go a bit further with the moves and discover together what is what in the O'Kelly Variation. }
3. c3
{ Going for the delayed Alapin Variation! We are threatening to play d4 and recapture with the pawn, and create a strong center. The point is that 2. Nf3 is a common move in the Alapin for White, while 2...a6 by Black is not what you normally spend your time on!   Black has many ways to play here, but the most critical one is 3...d5, where the inclusion of 2...a6 is not that much felt. In the other lines White gets a considerable advantage. }
3... d5
{ Is the best version of the Alapin that Black can get. It has the plus that it avoids Na3-Nb5 lines since a6 is on the board, and the presence of a6 is kind of useful in the Isolated Queen's Pawn positions that are arising.   The main point of this move is that White will no longer get a nice pawn center even though Black has to develop the Queen early, this is balancing with the fact that the pawn on c3 is blocking the b1 Knight at the moment. }
4. exd5 { The only ambitious move, forcing Black to develop the Queen early. }
4... Qxd5
{ The main move, going for a traditional Alapin where the a6 move is pretty useful compared to what we have seen so far. }
5. d4 Nf6 6. Be3 { Threatening to take on c5. } 6... cxd4 7. cxd4
{ We are entering an Isolated Queen's Pawn type of position. This means that we have to come up with active play to compensate the structural weakness. On the bright side, White has easy development by going Nc3-Bd3-O-O-Rc1, and then he can try to set up the battery by going Bb1 and Qd3 with pressure on the enemy King-side.   As a small tip, I recommend to go a3 whenever Black plays Nc6, because this way there will be no Nb4-Nd5 ideas to maneuver the Knight. Also as White we generally don't want to trade Queens, unless we are winning something. }
7... e6 { The most solid move, played by Artemiev, and other Grandmasters. } 8.
Nc3 Qd6 9. Bd3
{ This is the best square for the Bishop, preparing to set-up the battery at some point with Bb1 and Qd3. }
9... Nc6 10. a3
{ I like this move once Black plays Nc6 because we are avoiding any Nb4-Nd5 ideas. }
10... Be7 11. O-O O-O 12. Rc1
{ ½- @@StartBracket@@22@@EndBracket@@ ½ @@StartBracket@@58@@EndBracket@@ Jensen,C @@StartBracket@@2377@@EndBracket@@-Szabo,R @@StartBracket@@2312@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2014 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Quickstarter"]
[Black "Nimzowitsch Variation "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Nimzowitsch Variation, or how I like to call it, the most underrated sideline of the Sicilian! This is the pet line of GM Rakhmanov. Although he has a lot of games with it, most of the players are using it as a surprise weapon, so you just have to be prepared with the common knowledge that I am about to teach you, because you never really know when you are about to face this line.   From my personal experience, back in the days where the lockdown was not a thing, I was playing a Latvian International Master, working hard trying to refute his System against the Ruy Lopez the whole morning. When we've got to the board, not only but he played the Sicilian, he went for this exact Nimzowitsch Variation! Of course I was not well prepared against it and I replied with   3.Nc3  trying to remember a move by move line that I studied ages ago. The game was very complicated and ended in a draw. The good news is that I summed up some key ideas that you can use in order to play this opening properly without relying on move-by-move stuff! }
3. e5 { The most principled reaction, taking space with tempo. } 3... Nd5 4.
Nc3
{ I like this move because it's inviting a strategical game.   4.d4  has been also played a lot, trying to directly refute Black's set-up. First of all, I don't think that is the refutation, and second, it is not a very practical approach because as I said, this is a surprise weapon, and it's not smart to do a memory contest with someone that looked it up that morning. }
4... Nxc3
{ Rakhmanov's Pet Line, entering a complex pawn structure. The danger of working on this line is that any random engine would show you +0.5 with any move, but we have to go a little bit deeper with it. First of all you can ask yourself, why is a 2680 GM playing this line for more than 20 times knowing that the engine gives White +0.5, and his opponents can prepare against it? Is he deliberately trying to get an inferior position or is it that he thinks the positions are definitely not as easy as they seem? }
5. dxc3
{ Let's pause here for a bit and talk about this pawn structure. As a small tip, I highly encourage you to learn pawn structures if you are trying to improve your chess. Knowing ideas and plans, understanding which pieces you should trade and which you shouldn't will really step up your game, instead of only learning concrete moves. Notice that I am making this course's ideas and set-ups based so you can play it without knowing a lot of move by move theory. Of course, there is always a little bit that you should know, but if you compare it with other lines, this study has more or less no concrete lines in it. Yes, knowing theory is good and it makes the difference sometimes, but keep in mind that your opponent has a big choice of openings and you should be prepared against everything.  Coming back to the current position, we have a pretty tricky situation. At first, it seems that White will castle long, Black will castle short and then White will probably play something like h4-Bd3-Bxh7 followed by Ng5 and kill Black on the King-side. This is a possible outcome but in fact Black is not forced to castle, neither on the King-side nor on the Queen-side! Black can wait for a while and stay with his King in the center since there is no way for White to open up the position. Taking that into consideration, it would be naive to castle long thinking Black will go short and we can mate him. Black will actually wait with the King in the center and try to attack us with plans such as a6-b5-b4, the c8 Bishop going to b7, the Knight to c6 and the Rook to c8, giving Black a strong initiative. Now that we know what Black is up to, we can actually outsmart him by waiting for Black to castle first, since White has more space and more useful moves! }
5... Nc6 6. Bf4 Qb6 { Rakhmanov's favorite move! } 7. b3
{ The most flexible keeping options to castle on both sides! } 7... Qc7 8. Qd2
e6 9. h4
{ Taking space on the King-side is always a good idea, whether if Black castles long or short. }
9... h6 10. h5
{ Notice that White is improving the position while waiting to see what Black is up to. }
10... b6 11. Bd3 { Staying flexible is the best! Not showing our plan yet! }
11... Bb7 12. Be4 O-O-O 13. O-O-O
{ Now that Black's King is on the Queen-Side we are not afraid of any a6-b5 storm!: 1-0  @@StartBracket@@42@@EndBracket@@ Velicka,P @@StartBracket@@2483@@EndBracket@@-Rakhmanov,A @@StartBracket@@2590@@EndBracket@@ La Pobla de Lillet 2010 }
*

