{ Going for the Rossolimo! I've decided to pick this opening because it's giving us the following advantages:    • We avoid a lot of complex theory    • We are going to have a strategical battle @@StartBracket@@most Sicilian players are very gifted tactical players!@@EndBracket@@    • We are going to be better prepared than our opponent @@StartBracket@@most of the players are focusing on the Open Sicilians, not on Anti-Sicilians.@@EndBracket@@    • We are still playing for an opening advantage, the Rossolimo is the main weapon of top players such as Fabiano Caruana, Magnus Carlsen, Levon Aronian, Viswanathan Anand, Michael Adams, and many more. }
3... e6
{ A very dynamical line! We can draw this conclusion by looking at the main ambassadors of this line: the Magician from Riga - Alexei Shirov, and ''El Niño'' from Baku - Teimour Radjabov, both known for their hyper aggressive play-style. I think this line reached it's peak in 2012 when Boris Gelfand used it 3 times, in his World Championship match with Vishy Anand. From that point the line has not been repeated in a World Championship Match, but it's still played quite often at all levels. Black prepares to bring his King's Knight to e7 and then to put the question to White's Bishop, with the move ... a7-a6. In this case, the exchange on c6 will be favorable for Black, because he will recapture with the Knight and keep a healthy pawn structure. }
4. Bxc6
{ This is the move which Viacheslav Andreevich Chebanenko used to recommend to his pupils. Nothing is attacking the Bishop on b5, but nevertheless, White voluntarily exchanges it for the Knight. Now a very interesting position arises, with Black having doubled pawns. In addition, in this structure, he will not find it easy to activate his Bishop on c8. }
4... bxc6 5. d3
{ I decided to pick this line over 5.b3 that was played in the match for the World Crown in 2012 between Anand and Gelfand. The point of 5.d3 is that we are solidifying the e4 pawn, and we are staying flexible with the Bishop. You will see that in some positions it makes sense to go for b3-Bb2. }
5... Ne7 { The old main line. } 6. Qe2
{ They teach you to develop the Queen last, so what is wrong with me that I am even adding an ''!'' to this move?! Well, here is the thing: the general rule is correct, and it applies in most of the cases, but unlike maths, chess is a sport, not a science. 6.Qe2 is a multi-purpose move, preparing to play e5 in some positions taking control over the dark squares, but most important, is that White stays flexible and is waiting for Black to commit, so for example once Black goes for Ng6, we are immediately pushing the h-pawn down the board! }
6... Ng6
{ We have to pay attention now because Black is threatening to play e5! and then d6, to activate the c8 Bishop! }
7. h4
{ This should be the first thing that pops out to your mind when you see a Knight on g6! Most of the times you will force Black to play h5 and weaken the g5 square, or if he doesn't react, you can kick that Knight with h5, and put him in an awkward situation. }
7... h5 8. e5
{ ''Removing peg by peg!'' – a Romanian saying meaning that we are combating fire with fire! Black was threatening to play e5, and open up the c8 Bishop, so actually 8.e5! is a prophylactic move directed against the light-squared Bishop. }
8... f6
{ Black is trying to challenge our center, but now you can see better why h4-h5 was a good inclusion for White: }
9. Qe4
{ Speculating that the Knight is not defended on g6, now Black has to make an awkward move to defend the Knight. }
9... Kf7 { A sad necessity, but the lesser evil. } 10. Na3
{ It is better to go via this route to c4, because if you go for the other route @@StartBracket@@Nd2-Nc4@@EndBracket@@ the c1 Bishop will be closed for one move. In our case, it might not make a huge difference, but in other scenarios, the small details are making the difference. }
10... d5 11. exd6
{ The Key move behind our strategy! Now Black has to deal with doubled isolated pawns on the c-file. }
11... Qxd6 12. Nc4 { Attacking the Queen. } 12... Qd5 13. Ne3
{ Offering a Queen trade in our terms! If Black wants to get rid of the Queens, he has to remain with the ugly pawn structure! }
13... Qxe4 14. dxe4
{ Let's analyze this endgame, because the strategy is important in this type of positions, because White is better with a lot of moves, but the overall strategy is important to maximize your chances to convert. At first glance it looks like a symmetrical position: Black has the doubled isolated pawns, but on the other hand he has the Bishop Pair, so you may think that the situation is pretty balanced. Now that we dive a little bit deeper in the position, we can notice that the Bishop Pair is not an important factor here since the f8 Bishop is restricted by its own pawns, and also the c8 Bishop is lacking a useful diagonal. Now that we clarified that the Bishop Pair is not an asset in this position, we see that Black is left with the double isolated pawns on the c-file. As a long term plan for White, the Bishop will be nicely placed on a3, from where it attacks the c5 pawn. The King will castle Queen-side, and the f3 Knight will be maneuvered to c4 via d2. }
14... e5
{ We will keep this move as the main line because it was played by the Magician of Riga, Alexei Shirov. }
15. g3 { A solid positional move, not allowing any Nf4 jumps. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Quickstarter"]
[Black "Rossolimo 3...d6 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ Going for the Rossolimo! I've decided to pick this opening because it's giving us the following advantages:    • We avoid a lot of complex theory    • We are going to have a strategical battle @@StartBracket@@most Sicilian players are very gifted tactical players!@@EndBracket@@    • We are going to be better prepared than our opponent @@StartBracket@@most of the players are focusing on the Open Sicilians, not on Anti-Sicilians.@@EndBracket@@    • We are still playing for an opening advantage, the Rossolimo is the main weapon of top players such as Fabiano Caruana, Magnus Carlsen, Levon Aronian, Viswanathan Anand, Michael Adams, and many more. }
3... d6 4. O-O Bd7 5. Re1 { Creating a square for the Bishop on f1. } 5... Nf6
6. h3
{ An interesting move order, if White goes   6.c3  a6  7.Bf1  Black usually follows up with the solid  7...Bg4  . }
6... a6 7. Bf1 { The safest square. } 7... e5 8. c3 Be7 9. d4
{ Grabbing space in the center. } 9... Qc7 10. d5
{ Attacking the Knight, winning more space. } 10... Nd8 11. a4
{ Threatening a5. } 11... b6 12. Na3
{ White has the simple plan of improving the Bishop with Bd3, and then play for f4 with Nh2-f4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Quickstarter"]
[Black "Westerinen Attack #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3
{ Going for The Westerinen Attack! Usually you don't see the Bishop going to the a1-h8 diagonal in the Sicilian Defense when playing the White pieces, but against 2...e6 I think that 3.b3 is a nice line to play because Black can't challenge the Bishop. The reason why you are not seeing b3 lines against the Sicilian that often, is because Black can block the diagonal most of the times and kill your b2 Bishop, as for example let's say you are trying to do the same set-up against 2...d6 by going 3.b3 and in some cases it might transpose to our line, but the main issue is that Black gets the extra option to block the diagonal with 3...e5!   The same reasoning applies against 2...Nc6, if you try 3.b3 Black has the strong 3...e5 blocking the b2 Bishop. Now that you understand what is the problem of the Queen-side Fianchetto against the other second moves, you can notice easier that the Bishop on b2 is having a good time against the 2...e6 Sicilian because Black is lacking a good way to block that strong piece. }
3... d6
{ The point of this move is to prepare Nf6 without allowing White to get e5 with tempo. The drawback of d6 is that we are going to play e5 anyway and the support the e5 Knight with f4! Then White has an easy plan of developing the light squared Bishop to d3, and the bring the Knight over to c4 via a3. If Black really wants to avoid that, he must go for 4...e5, trying to block our b2 Bishop, but White end up on top after 5. Bb5+ with the simple and straightforward plan of going short castle, and c3-d4 to break the center. }
4. Bb2 { Developing the Bishop. } 4... Nc6
{ This is also a very popular line for Black! The point is to play Nf6 next and prevent us from getting e5 and then to support the Knight with f4. It is a smart way for Black to avoid our e5 attacking line, but we have a surprisingly strong continuation here! We can just go for 5.d4! here, going for an Open Sicilian position with the simple and straightforward plan of going Nc3-Qd2-0-0-0 and push the King-side pawns! }
5. d4
{ We are entering a favorable variation of the Open Sicilian. This is resembling the modern system with 2.Nc3 and Qxd4-Qd2 and b3-Bb2, 0-0-0, that is now very popular against the Najdorf. }
5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 { Recapturing the pawn. } 6... Nf6 7. Nc3
{ Developing the Knight, preparing Qd2 and 0-0-0. } 7... Be7 8. Qd2
{ Developing the Queen, preparing 0-0-0. } 8... O-O 9. O-O-O
{ Getting the King to safety before starting the attack. } 9... a6 10. Kb1
{ Always a strong move after castling long. } 10... Qc7 11. g4
{ Sacrificing the pawn for a quick attack! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Quickstarter"]
[Black "Westerinen Attack #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3
{ Going for The Westerinen Attack! Usually you don't see the Bishop going to the a1-h8 diagonal in the Sicilian Defense when playing the White pieces, but against 2...e6 I think that 3.b3 is a nice line to play because Black can't challenge the Bishop. The reason why you are not seeing b3 lines against the Sicilian that often, is because Black can block the diagonal most of the times and kill your b2 Bishop, as for example let's say you are trying to do the same set-up against 2...d6 by going 3.b3 and in some cases it might transpose to our line, but the main issue is that Black gets the extra option to block the diagonal with 3...e5!   The same reasoning applies against 2...Nc6, if you try 3.b3 Black has the strong 3...e5 blocking the b2 Bishop. Now that you understand what is the problem of the Queen-side Fianchetto against the other second moves, you can notice easier that the Bishop on b2 is having a good time against the 2...e6 Sicilian because Black is lacking a good way to block that strong piece. }
3... d6
{ The point of this move is to prepare Nf6 without allowing White to get e5 with tempo. The drawback of d6 is that we are going to play e5 anyway and the support the e5 Knight with f4! Then White has an easy plan of developing the light squared Bishop to d3, and the bring the Knight over to c4 via a3. If Black really wants to avoid that, he must go for 4...e5, trying to block our b2 Bishop, but White end up on top after 5. Bb5+ with the simple and straightforward plan of going short castle, and c3-d4 to break the center. }
4. Bb2 { Developing the Bishop. } 4... Nf6
{ The main move for this move order. Black simply wants to play Be7 and castle short. }
5. e5
{ The point of this line! We are not going to allow Black to get away with it. }
5... dxe5 6. Nxe5 { Recapturing the pawn. } 6... Nbd7 7. f4
{ The big point of the line, not allowing Black to simply trade our strong Knight and then finish his development easily. If Black really wants to get rid of our Knight now, he has to bring our pawn to the e5 square, taking away the f6 square of the Knight, and give us attacking chances on the King-side. If Black does not take the e5 Knight, we are going to develop our light squared Bishop on d3, bring the Knight to c4 via a3, and depending on the exact situation, 0-0 with the famous Rook lift Rf3-Rh3 should give us strong attack. }
7... Be7 8. Bd3 { White's Bishops are ready to hunt the King-side. } 8... O-O
9. O-O { Getting our King to safety. } 9... Qc7 10. a4
{ A strong positional move, preparing to bring the Knight to c4! } 10... a6 11.
Na3 { Developing the Knight, heading to c4. } 11... b6 12. Rf3
{ Preparing to swing the Rook to the King-side. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Quickstarter"]
[Black "Westerinen Attack #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3
{ Going for The Westerinen Attack! Usually you don't see the Bishop going to the a1-h8 diagonal in the Sicilian Defense when playing the White pieces, but against 2...e6 I think that 3.b3 is a nice line to play because Black can't challenge the Bishop. The reason why you are not seeing b3 lines against the Sicilian that often, is because Black can block the diagonal most of the times and kill your b2 Bishop, as for example let's say you are trying to do the same set-up against 2...d6 by going 3.b3 and in some cases it might transpose to our line, but the main issue is that Black gets the extra option to block the diagonal with 3...e5!   The same reasoning applies against 2...Nc6, if you try 3.b3 Black has the strong 3...e5 blocking the b2 Bishop. Now that you understand what is the problem of the Queen-side Fianchetto against the other second moves, you can notice easier that the Bishop on b2 is having a good time against the 2...e6 Sicilian because Black is lacking a good way to block that strong piece. }
3... d5
{ It is a very principled approach by Black to play in the center because our previous move is a little bit slow. Nevertheless, we are happy to see this move on the board because we are going to have an Isolated Queen's Pawn type of position, where we get to trade the light-squared Bishops with 5.Bb5+! Trading the light-squared Bishops is helping White a lot because the isolated pawn on d5 will be much weaker without Black having a Bishop on e6 to defend it. Black can try to avoid this scenario by going 5...Nc6, and not trade the Bishops, but then he is running into concrete problems after the annoying check 6.Qe2+! You have to be careful with the move orders as White, but I think the reward is good enough if you do it. }
4. exd5 { Taking the pawn. } 4... exd5 5. Bb5+
{ An important check, threatening to trade the light squared Bishops and preparing 0-0. }
5... Bd7 { The main move in this position. } 6. Bxd7+ { Taking the Bishop. }
6... Nxd7 7. O-O { Getting our King to safety. } 7... Bd6 8. Bb2
{ Developing the Bishop, attacking g7. } 8... f6 9. d4
{ Breaking the center, preparing to play against the isolani. } 9... Ne7 10.
Nc3 { Developing the Knight. } 10... O-O 11. Nxd5
{ A cute tactic to win a pawn. } 11... Nxd5 12. dxc5
{ White will win back the piece with and remain a pawn up. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Quickstarter"]
[Black "Westerinen Attack #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3
{ Going for The Westerinen Attack! Usually you don't see the Bishop going to the a1-h8 diagonal in the Sicilian Defense when playing the White pieces, but against 2...e6 I think that 3.b3 is a nice line to play because Black can't challenge the Bishop. The reason why you are not seeing b3 lines against the Sicilian that often, is because Black can block the diagonal most of the times and kill your b2 Bishop, as for example let's say you are trying to do the same set-up against 2...d6 by going 3.b3 and in some cases it might transpose to our line, but the main issue is that Black gets the extra option to block the diagonal with 3...e5!   The same reasoning applies against 2...Nc6, if you try 3.b3 Black has the strong 3...e5 blocking the b2 Bishop. Now that you understand what is the problem of the Queen-side Fianchetto against the other second moves, you can notice easier that the Bishop on b2 is having a good time against the 2...e6 Sicilian because Black is lacking a good way to block that strong piece. }
3... b6
{ Is what the stronger players are doing. I doubt that you will encounter this line if your opponent is under 2000 level. The point of this move is to play Bb7 next, making it awkward for White to defend the e4 pawn. This is a subtle move, and is going to be played only by a well-prepared opponent. The big advantage is that even strong Grandmasters are not always going for what I consider to be Black's best chance! Okay, now what if Black goes for it? I recommend you to open up the position with 4.d4 on the next move, and after 4...cxd4 5.Nxd4 Bb7 I managed to come up with a new way of handling this line: 6.Nd2!? }
4. d4
{ Opening up the position. The point is to have Nd2 when Black plays Bb7. }
4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 { Recapturing the pawn. } 5... Bb7
{ By far the most natural, and the most played move in this position. } 6. Nd2
{ My fresh approach of the position! Everyone used to play 6.Bd3 in this position, but that would have allowed Black to go for the line with 6...Bc5 7. Bb2 and now Black has the strong 7...Qf6! forcing White to play the awkward move 8.c3 to defend the Knight. So what is the difference between 6.Bd3 and 6. Nd2 you may be asking yourself? The ideas behind 6.Nd2 are pretty similar to 6. Bd3 if Black plays normal developing moves, White gets a comfortable game with moves such as: Bb2-Bd3-0-0-f4, and maybe even c4 is nice sometimes to set-up the ''Hedgehog structure''. As a rule of thumb whenever Black plays Nc6 we are replying with Nxc6 to open up the diagonal of the b2 Bishop. Now the big difference is that none of this would be possible as i mentioned earlier, because Black can go for 7...Qf6! and kill the 6.Bd3 line. If Black tries to to the same against 6.Nd2, let's say 6...Bc5, we defend the Knight with 7.Bb2 and if Black tries to go for the same 7...Qf6, this is no longer effective because White has the extra option of going 8.Nc4! with initiative. }
6... Nf6 { The natural move, gives us a pleasant position. } 7. Bd3
{ Developing the Bishop, defending the e4 pawn. } 7... Be7 8. Qe2
{ Developing the Queen. } 8... O-O 9. Bb2 { Developing the Bishop. } 9... Nc6
10. Nxc6 { Taking the Knight. } 10... Bxc6 11. O-O
{ I personally like short castle, but you can go for 0-0-0 if you are feeling adventurous. }
11... Qc7 12. f4 { Grabbing space, preparing Rf3-Rh3. } 12... d6 13. Kh1
{ White has easy play on the King-side connected with the Rook lift to h3, and pushing e5 at some point. Westerinen Attack-Summary  @@StartSquare@@Banzea,Alex@@EndSquare@@ }
*

