{ Going for the sharpest line possible because a6 is useless! } 6... Nb6 7. Bb3
d5 8. exd6 { Opening it up. } 8... e6 9. Qxd4
{ Keeping an eye on g7, not allowing Black to recapture on d6 with the Bishop. }
9... Qxd6 10. Qh4 { Keeping the Queens on! } 10... Qd3 11. Nd4
{ Threatening to play Bc2 and get rid of that Queen. } 11... Qg6 12. O-O Be7
13. Qf4 N8d7 14. Bc2 Nd5 15. Qf3 Qf6 16. Qd1
{ Again avoiding the trade because we can play for an attack later, and Black's Queen is misplaced on f6. }
16... O-O 17. Re1 Nc5 18. Nd2
{ White has multiple ways to develop, one of them is N2f3 with the threat of going Bg5. }
*

