{ Is leading to the French Defense type of structure. The presence of a6 on the board is not that big of a deal. Of course it would have been better for Black to have a choice between Bd7  @@StartBracket@@ the Euwe Variation @@EndBracket@@  or other main line with Nge7, so in that way Black is not very flexible. White still has to come up with a plan to develop and maintain a solid center. I recommend to put the Bishop on d3 because it's the most active square. }
5... Bd7 6. Bd3 Nc6
{ As a general strategy White is developing accordingly to the center, the b1 Knight goes on c3 if Black takes on d4 quickly, but if Black tries to postpone capturing on d4 I recommend dxc5! solving the problem of the b1 Knight, that will be heading to d4 via Nd2-Nb3-Nbd4. }
7. O-O
{ Now Black is at a crossroads. He can choose whether he is going after the d4 pawn, or if he continues to develop: }
7... cxd4
{ Going for concrete play in the center is something very common especially when the Bishop is on d3, as the d4 pawn is slightly vulnerable. }
8. cxd4 Qb6 9. Be2 { Clearing the path of the Queen to the d4 square. } 9...
Rc8 10. Nc3 Nge7 11. Na4
{ An important move, preparing to develop with Be3, without hanging the pawn on b2. }
11... Qa7 12. Be3
{ This might look a bit odd because the Bishop is kind of staring into the d4 pawn, but it is very important to guard that pawn! }
12... Nf5 13. Bd3
{ Threatening to take the Knight, and inviting Black to take on e3! } 13...
Nxe3 14. fxe3
{ White has a very solid center and is going to slowly but steady build up the pressure with moves such as Rc1-Nc5. }
*

