1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 a6
{ The O'Kelly Sicilian has arrived on the board! This is a very tricky variation for White because the Open Sicilian does not work well here, as you can see in the upcoming notes. I used this line myself when I started chess about 10 years ago with very decent results against club players, because nobody knew how to react against it.  Back then it was considered to be a somewhat dubious line for Black and it was rarely seen in Grand Master games. Nowadays this line has become very popular even at the 2600+ level mainly because of Vladislav Artemiev playing it in more than 20 games.  Why is this line becoming more and more popular nowadays? Well, I would say the fact that you play the Sicilian as Black and White can't go for the Open Sicilian is pretty powerful. Back in the day, people had a superficial opinion about this variation because it was considered that after either  3.c4  or  3.c3  White gets a free advantage.  As theory has advanced, I invite you to go a bit further with the moves and discover together what is what in the O'Kelly Variation. }
3. c3
{ Going for the delayed Alapin Variation! We are threatening to play d4 and recapture with the pawn, and create a strong center. The point is that 2.Nf3 is a common move in the Alapin for White, while 2...a6 by Black is not what you normally spend your time on!  Black has many ways to play here, but the most critical one is  3.--  ...d5  , where the inclusion of 2...a6 is not that much felt. In the other lines White gets a considerable advantage. }
3... d5
{ Is the best version of the Alapin that Black can get. It has the plus that it avoids Na3-Nb5 lines since a6 is on the board, and the presence of a6 is kind of useful in the Isolated Queen's Pawn positions that are arising. The main point of this move is that White will no longer get a nice pawn center even though Black has to develop the Queen early, this is balancing with the fact that the pawn on c3 is blocking the b1 Knight at the moment. }
4. exd5 { The only ambitious move, forcing Black to develop the Queen early. }
4... Qxd5
{ The main move, going for a traditional Alapin where the a6 move is pretty useful compared to what we have seen so far. }
5. d4 Nf6 6. Be3 { Threatening to take on c5. } 6... cxd4 7. cxd4
{ We are entering an Isolated Queen's Pawn type of position. This means that we have to come up with active play to compensate for the structural weakness. On the bright side, White has easy development by going Nc3-Bd3-O-O-Rc1, and then he can try to set up the battery by going Bb1 and Qd3 with pressure on the enemy King-side. As a small tip, I recommend to go a3 whenever Black plays Nc6, because this way there will be no Nb4-Nd5 ideas to maneuver the Knight. Also as White we generally don't want to trade Queens, unless we are winning something. }
7... e6 { The most solid move, played by Artemiev, and other Grand Masters. }
8. Nc3 Qd6 9. Bd3
{ This is the best square for the Bishop, preparing to set-up the battery at some point with Bb1 and Qd3. }
9... Nc6 10. a3
{ I like this move once Black plays Nc6 because we are avoiding any Nb4-Nd5 ideas. }
10... Be7 11. O-O O-O 12. Rc1 Rd8
{ This is the tricky line and what you have to remember! Here the Bb1 plan is too slow because Black is in time with e5! }
13. Bb1 e5 { Black's main idea. } *

