1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Nimzowitsch Variation, or how I like to call it, the most underrated sideline of the Sicilian! This is the pet line of GM Rakhmanov. Although he has a lot of games with it, most of the players are using it as a surprise weapon, so you just have to be prepared with the common knowledge that I am about to teach you, because you never really know when you are about to face this line. From my personal experience I was playing a Latvian International Master back in the days where the lockdown was not a thing, and I was working hard trying to refute his System against the Ruy Lopez the whole morning, and when we've got to the board, not only he played the Sicilian, but he went for this exact Nimzowitsch Variation! Of course, I was not well prepared against it and I replied with  3.Nc3  trying to remember a move by move line that I studied ages ago. The game was very complicated and ended in a draw. The good news is that I summed up some key ideas that you can use in order to play this opening properly without relying on move-by-move stuff! }
3. e5 { The most principled reaction, taking space with tempo. } 3... Nd5 4.
Nc3
{ I like this move because it's inviting a strategical game.  4.d4  has been also played a lot, trying to directly refute Black's set-up. First of all, I don't think that is the refutation, and second, it is not a very practical approach because as I said, this is a surprise weapon, and it's not smart to do a memory contest with someone that looked it up that morning. }
4... e6
{ Has been the most played move in this position, but never used by the biggest expert of the line, Rakhmanov.That was a sign for me that something smelled fishy with this line, and then i figured out that the less popular move of White is the best here: }
5. Ne4
{ Everyone is playing  5.Nxd5  in this position, but that is not the best! I believe this exact move is the reason why Rakhmanov never played 4...e6, White gets a strong initiative after 5.Ne4! }
5... f5 { Black's best bet in this position. } 6. Nc3
{ But we have this strong retreat! The point is that now Nxd5 is going to be a better version for White with the pawn on f5! }
6... Nxc3 7. dxc3
{ Here we have a similar pawn structure with the Main Line, but the huge difference is that Black has f5 on the board which is a permanent hook that White can use by playing g4 at some point. }
7... Nc6 8. Bf4 Qb6 9. b3 { The standard reaction. } 9... Qc7 10. Qd2 Be7 11.
O-O-O
{ We are not afraid of any Queen-side storm here because we have our own play on the King-side connected with g4! }
11... a6 12. Rg1 { Preparing g4. } 12... h6 13. h4 { Stopping g5. } 13... h5
{ It looks like Black stops White's initiative for the moment but here White has a powerful plan: }
14. Rh1 b5 15. Rh3
{ A nice regroupment by White, and a fine victory in the game: 1-0 @@StartBracket@@51@@EndBracket@@ Van Kampen,R @@StartBracket@@2475@@EndBracket@@-Swinkels,R @@StartBracket@@2495@@EndBracket@@ Wijk aan Zee 2010 }
