[White "4. Nimzowitsch Variation: 2...Nf6!?"]
[Black "4.Nc3 Nxc3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Nimzowitsch Variation, or how I like to call it, the most underrated sideline of the Sicilian! This is the pet line of GM Rakhmanov. Although he has a lot of games with it, most of the players are using it as a surprise weapon, so you just have to be prepared with the common knowledge that I am about to teach you, because you never really know when you are about to face this line. From my personal experience I was playing a Latvian International Master back in the days where the lockdown was not a thing, and I was working hard trying to refute his System against the Ruy Lopez the whole morning, and when we've got to the board, not only he played the Sicilian, but he went for this exact Nimzowitsch Variation! Of course, I was not well prepared against it and I replied with  3.Nc3  trying to remember a move by move line that I studied ages ago. The game was very complicated and ended in a draw. The good news is that I summed up some key ideas that you can use in order to play this opening properly without relying on move-by-move stuff! }
3. e5 { The most principled reaction, taking space with tempo. } 3... Nd5 4.
Nc3
{ I like this move because it's inviting a strategical game.  4.d4  has been also played a lot, trying to directly refute Black's set-up. First of all, I don't think that is the refutation, and second, it is not a very practical approach because as I said, this is a surprise weapon, and it's not smart to do a memory contest with someone that looked it up that morning. }
4... Nxc3
{ Rakhmanov's Pet Line, entering a complex pawn structure. The danger of working on this line is that any random engine would show you +0.5 with any move, but we have to go a little bit deeper with it. First of all you can ask yourself, why is a 2680 GM @@StartBracket@@Rakhmanov@@EndBracket@@ playing this line for more than 20 times knowing that the engine gives White +0.5, and his opponents can prepare against it? Is he deliberately trying to get an inferior position or is it that he thinks the positions are definitely not as easy as they seem? }
5. dxc3
{ Let's pause here for a bit and talk about this pawn structure. As a small tip, I highly encourage you to learn pawn structures if you are trying to improve your chess. Knowing ideas and plans, understanding what pieces you should trade and what you shouldn't will really step up your game, instead of only learning concrete moves. Notice that I am making this course's ideas and set-ups based so you can play it without knowing a lot of move by move theory. Of course, there is always a little bit that you should know, but if you compare it with other lines, this study has more or less no concrete lines in it. Yes, knowing theory is good and it makes the difference sometimes, but keep in mind that your opponent has a big choice of openings and you should be prepared against everything.    Coming back to the current position, we have a pretty tricky situation. At first it seems that White will castle long, Black will castle short and then White will probably play something like h4-Bd3-Bxh7 followed by Ng5 and kill Black on the King-side. This is a possible outcome, but in fact Black is not forced to castle, neither on the King-side, nor on the Queen-side! Black can wait for a while and stay with his King in the center because there is no way for White to open up the position. So taking that into consideration, it would be naive to castle long thinking Black will go short castle and we can mate him. Black will actually wait with the King in the center and try to attack us with plans such as a6-b5-b4, the c8 Bishop goes on b7, the Knight goes on c6 and the Rook comes on c8, giving Black a strong initiative. So now that we know what Black is up to, we can actually outsmart him by waiting for Black to castle first, since White has more space, and more useful moves! }
5... Nc6 6. Bf4 e6 { I think it's just a better version for White: } 7. Qd2 h6
8. h4 { Taking space and stopping g5 ideas. } 8... a6 9. h5 b5 10. a4
{ Now we can just attack on the Queen-side after Black commits with b5. } 10...
b4 11. Bd3 Bb7 12. c4 Na5 13. Qe2 d5 14. cxd5 Qxd5 15. b3
{ White stops all the Queen-side counterplay! } 15... Be7 16. Rh3
{ White is better here because Black has weak pawn on a6 that he needs to take care of, plus White can also Rook-lift. }
*

