{ Let's pause here for a bit and talk about this pawn structure. As a small tip, I highly encourage you to learn pawn structures if you are trying to improve your chess. Knowing ideas and plans, understanding what pieces you should trade and what you shouldn't will really step up your game, instead of only learning concrete moves. Notice that I am making this course's ideas and set-ups based so you can play it without knowing a lot of move by move theory. Of course, there is always a little bit that you should know, but if you compare it with other lines, this study has more or less no concrete lines in it. Yes, knowing theory is good and it makes the difference sometimes, but keep in mind that your opponent has a big choice of openings and you should be prepared against everything.    Coming back to the current position, we have a pretty tricky situation. At first it seems that White will castle long, Black will castle short and then White will probably play something like h4-Bd3-Bxh7 followed by Ng5 and kill Black on the King-side. This is a possible outcome, but in fact Black is not forced to castle, neither on the King-side, nor on the Queen-side! Black can wait for a while and stay with his King in the center because there is no way for White to open up the position. So taking that into consideration, it would be naive to castle long thinking Black will go short castle and we can mate him. Black will actually wait with the King in the center and try to attack us with plans such as a6-b5-b4, the c8 Bishop goes on b7, the Knight goes on c6 and the Rook comes on c8, giving Black a strong initiative. So now that we know what Black is up to, we can actually outsmart him by waiting for Black to castle first, since White has more space, and more useful moves! }
5... Nc6 6. Bf4 Qb6 { Rakhmanov's favorite move! } 7. b3
{ The most flexible keeping options to castle on both sides! } 7... Qc7 8. Qd2
e6 9. h4
{ Taking space on the King-side is always a good idea, whether if Black castles long or short. }
9... h6 10. h5
{ Notice that White is improving the position while waiting to see what Black is up to. }
10... b6 11. Bd3 { Staying flexible is the best!Not showing our plan yet! }
11... Bb7 12. Be4 Ne7 13. Bxb7 Qxb7 14. Qe2 Nd5 15. Bd2 Be7 16. c4
{ Now that we get rid of the central Knight, Black will not have a lot to be proud of. }
16... Nb4 17. Bf4 Qc7 18. c3 Nc6 19. Qe4
{ White will castle long and then play Rg1-g4. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Nimzowitsch Variation: 2...Nf6!?"]
[Black "4.Nc3 Nxc3 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Nimzowitsch Variation, or how I like to call it, the most underrated sideline of the Sicilian! This is the pet line of GM Rakhmanov. Although he has a lot of games with it, most of the players are using it as a surprise weapon, so you just have to be prepared with the common knowledge that I am about to teach you, because you never really know when you are about to face this line. From my personal experience I was playing a Latvian International Master back in the days where the lockdown was not a thing, and I was working hard trying to refute his System against the Ruy Lopez the whole morning, and when we've got to the board, not only he played the Sicilian, but he went for this exact Nimzowitsch Variation! Of course, I was not well prepared against it and I replied with  3.Nc3  trying to remember a move by move line that I studied ages ago. The game was very complicated and ended in a draw. The good news is that I summed up some key ideas that you can use in order to play this opening properly without relying on move-by-move stuff! }
3. e5 { The most principled reaction, taking space with tempo. } 3... Nd5 4.
Nc3
{ I like this move because it's inviting a strategical game.  4.d4  has been also played a lot, trying to directly refute Black's set-up. First of all, I don't think that is the refutation, and second, it is not a very practical approach because as I said, this is a surprise weapon, and it's not smart to do a memory contest with someone that looked it up that morning. }
4... Nxc3
{ Rakhmanov's Pet Line, entering a complex pawn structure. The danger of working on this line is that any random engine would show you +0.5 with any move, but we have to go a little bit deeper with it. First of all you can ask yourself, why is a 2680 GM @@StartBracket@@Rakhmanov@@EndBracket@@ playing this line for more than 20 times knowing that the engine gives White +0.5, and his opponents can prepare against it? Is he deliberately trying to get an inferior position or is it that he thinks the positions are definitely not as easy as they seem? }
5. dxc3
{ Let's pause here for a bit and talk about this pawn structure. As a small tip, I highly encourage you to learn pawn structures if you are trying to improve your chess. Knowing ideas and plans, understanding what pieces you should trade and what you shouldn't will really step up your game, instead of only learning concrete moves. Notice that I am making this course's ideas and set-ups based so you can play it without knowing a lot of move by move theory. Of course, there is always a little bit that you should know, but if you compare it with other lines, this study has more or less no concrete lines in it. Yes, knowing theory is good and it makes the difference sometimes, but keep in mind that your opponent has a big choice of openings and you should be prepared against everything.    Coming back to the current position, we have a pretty tricky situation. At first it seems that White will castle long, Black will castle short and then White will probably play something like h4-Bd3-Bxh7 followed by Ng5 and kill Black on the King-side. This is a possible outcome, but in fact Black is not forced to castle, neither on the King-side, nor on the Queen-side! Black can wait for a while and stay with his King in the center because there is no way for White to open up the position. So taking that into consideration, it would be naive to castle long thinking Black will go short castle and we can mate him. Black will actually wait with the King in the center and try to attack us with plans such as a6-b5-b4, the c8 Bishop goes on b7, the Knight goes on c6 and the Rook comes on c8, giving Black a strong initiative. So now that we know what Black is up to, we can actually outsmart him by waiting for Black to castle first, since White has more space, and more useful moves! }
5... Nc6 6. Bf4 Qb6 { Rakhmanov's favorite move! } 7. b3
{ The most flexible keeping options to castle on both sides! } 7... Qc7 8. Qd2
e6 9. h4
{ Taking space on the King-side is always a good idea, whether if Black castles long or short. }
9... h6 10. h5
{ Notice that White is improving the position while waiting to see what Black is up to. }
10... b6 11. Bd3 { Staying flexible is the best!Not showing our plan yet! }
11... Bb7 12. Be4 O-O-O 13. O-O-O
{ Now that Black's King is on the Queen-side we are not afraid of any a6-b5 storm! }
13... b5 { Is no longer that effective: } 14. Kb1 { Always play Kb1! } 14...
Ne7 15. Qe2 Bxe4 16. Qxe4 Qc6 17. Qxc6+
{ White is always better in the endgames, because he can press on the d file, or push the pawns on the King-side because of the space advantage created early on with h5. For an experienced player it is quite obvious that White has a big edge here because a simple plan such as pushing g4 and then f4-f5-f6 will probably Queen the h pawn. }
17... Nxc6 18. Nd2
{ With a more pleasant endgame for White in the game: 1-0 @@StartBracket@@42@@EndBracket@@ Velicka,P @@StartBracket@@2483@@EndBracket@@ -Rakhmanov,A @@StartBracket@@2590@@EndBracket@@ La Pobla de Lillet 2010 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. The Harikrishna System"]
[Black "Hungarian variation 7.b3 Be7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The most popular reply to 2.Nf3, Black is setting up a bunch of strong Sicilians such as: the Najdorf Sicilian, the Dragon Sicilian and the Classical Sicilian. I decided to tackle these bulls with the Hungarian Variation that is arising after  3.d4  cxd4  and now the Queen recapture  4.Qxd4!? }
3. d4 Nf6
{ Black can go for this move order, although it's not played that often as the main move, it's still very playable forcing White to go Nc3. This usually does not change much, but especially against our Hungarian, it takes away some options: for example, now it doesn't make any sense to analyze any c4 ideas in the Main Line and set up the Maroczy Bind if Black can avoid it by playing the smart move order with 3...Nf6. This move order is avoiding the c4 ideas, but we can go for the main plan that I am recommending with Nc3 and most likely transpose to the Main Line. }
4. Nc3 cxd4 5. Qxd4
{ Entering the Hungarian Variation, but with an early Nc3. By looking at the main lines, you can notice that we prefer to postpone this Nc3 move, and rush Be2-h3-O-O and Rd1 with the threat of going e5, and only after that we develop the Knight on c3. This might not be very relevant since there are big odds of just transposing to the Main Line, but I want you to pay attention because Black has a few extra options here. }
5... Nc6
{ Black could have also gone  5...a6  or  5...Bd7  .The point of those moves is to play Nc6 without allowing White to pin the Knight with Bb5. I haven't included them here since it's not bothering us, for we are going for our plan with Be2, Qe3, O-O, h3, Rd1 and you can see that these moves are not particularly threatening us. }
6. Qe3
{ Trying to play Be2, h3 and O-O with Rd1, transposing to the Main Line. Most often Black goes for   6...g6  here which is going to transpose to the Main Line, but let's see what happens if he tries to avoid it by playing  6...e6  or if he tries the early break in the center with 6...d5: }
6... e6 7. b3
{ I like this move because it reminds me of theWesterinen Attack! White wants to castle Queen-side and then play Rg1 with the idea of g4, throwing those pawns on to the enemy King. }
7... Be7 8. Bb2 O-O 9. O-O-O a6 10. Rg1 { Preparing g4 } 10... Ng4
{ Black is trying to be annoying. } 11. Qe1 b5 12. h3 Nge5 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. f4
Qb6 15. fxe5 { Sacrificing the exchange, for positional domination! } 15...
Qxg1 16. exd6 Bg5+ 17. Kb1
{ White gets a very dangerous passer for the exchange and nice control over the position. }
17... Qe3 18. Qxe3
{ We don't really mind the endgame, but you can avoid it by playing Be2 if you want. }
18... Bxe3 19. e5 Bb7 20. a4 b4 21. Ne2
{ Black always has to worry about the d6-pawn, while White can slowly chip away his Queen-side. }
*

