{ Taking advantage of the pin! } 7... dxe5
{ The main move by far, I never really faced the alternatives, but I did analyse them in case you might face any. }
8. Nxe5 { Increasing the pressure on the pinned Knight. } 8... Qd4
{ Is the ''easy way out''.Usually this move is played trying to bail out of any preparation, forcing the endgame, and trying to hold a slightly worse position. I think the best way for White to punish this is by taking on c6, and after the Queen trade, to play 11.b3! developing the Bishop on the long diagonal, and shutting down the enemy Fianchetto Bishop.After that White's position is statically better because of the healthier pawn structure from the Queen-side. }
9. Nxc6 Qxa4 10. Nxa4 bxc6 11. b3
{ I like to challenge the diagonal and go for Bb2 next. } 11... Bg7 12. Bb2 O-O
13. Bd3
{ White is flexible, not rushing to castle, keeping both options possible. }
13... Ng4 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. h3 Ne5 16. Be2 { Keeping the Bishop! } 16... Bf5
17. O-O-O { White is a slightly better with a nicer pawn structure. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Accelerated Dragon"]
[Black "Mainline 7.e5 dxe5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6
{ Going for the Accelerated Dragon! From my experience, the Black players are one-trick-pony of this opening and they know it very well. Thinking about the fact that you are going to face this opening less often than  2...Nc6  and  2...d6  it makes sense to recommend a line that is easy to play for White and you don't rely on move by move stuff that much. This is the most common move order for the Accelerated Dragon. Black can start by going  2...Nc6  and only after  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  to go for the King-side fianchetto with  4...g6  . This move order has the plus that it avoid the line that I am going to suggest for White but the drawback that it allows theRossolimo @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/1Bp5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq -@@EndFEN@@  3.Bb5
@@EndBracket@@. So it doesn't really matter what move order Black plays, you will be prepared against both. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4
{ This line was known to be harmless for Black after  4...Nf6  5.e5  , Black has enough counterplay after the move  5...Nc6  , White can try to continue with  6.Qa4  Nd5  7.Qe4  but Black has been doing more than okay after the move  7...Nb6  . This used to be the old main line, but nowadays White found out that the move  5.Nc3  , staying flexible is leading to a positional game when White usually grabs the Bishop Pair, or if Black wants to avoid the positional squeeze he is supposed to sacrifice a pawn with  8...Bg7!?  but this does not guarantee him an equal game. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3
{ The modern approach, picked up by a lot of strong Grand Masters.Now White is threatening to play e5 and then if Nc6 happens, White can safely go for Qa4, and there will be no Nd5 available for Black now since we already developed our Knight to c3! }
5... Nc6 6. Qa4
{ This is the key move! White is threatening to play e5 next, so to stop that, Black has to play  6...d6  @@StartBracket@@the other moves are just inferior@@EndBracket@@ and we can take advantage of the pinned Knight by going  7.e5!  . }
6... d6 { Is the best way to play against White's threat of going e5. } 7. e5
{ Taking advantage of the pin! } 7... dxe5
{ The main move by far, I never really faced the alternatives, but I did analyse them in case you might face any. }
8. Nxe5 { Increasing the pressure on the pinned Knight. } 8... Bg7
{ This is a pawn sacrifice, but Black has to be very precise in order to keep realistic compensation for the pawn!The toughest test for Black is the move 9. Bb5, taking the pawn with the Bishop.Then Black's best defence is to force the light squared Bishops off with the move 11... Bd7! This is what the biggest expert of the line, Gadir Guseinov played as Black and managed to hold.It is important for Black to trade the light squared Bishops because he can later use the light squares from the Queen-side to generate counterplay, especially the c4 square.Notice that if Black does not go for 11... Bd7 and plays 11... Rb8 instead, we are avoiding the Bishop trade! Nevertheless i think White still keeps a small edge even in that case with precise play! }
9. Bb5 { It's better to develop first, and take on c6 with the Bishop! } 9...
O-O 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Bxc6 Rb8
{ Feels natural, but it's actually in Black's favor to trade the light squared Bishops! }
12. O-O Bf5 13. Bb5 Qc7 14. Bf4 { Forcing e5, locking the Bishop on g7! } 14...
e5 15. Be3 Bxc2 16. Qxa7
{ This is just a worse Benko for Black with the closed Bishop on g7. } 16...
Rb7 17. Qa6 e4 18. Bf4 Qxf4
{ It's Black's best bet to try to sacrifice the exchange but White should be able to defend with a few accurate moves: }
19. Qxb7 Ng4 20. g3 Qh6 21. h4 e3 22. f4
{ Making sure that the Queen gets locked on h6! } 22... Bd4 23. Be2
{ Simply stopping the pawn. } 23... Nf2 24. a4
{ Now White can focus on his own play. } *

