{ Going for the Rossolimo! I've decided to pick this opening because it's giving us the following advantages:    • We are avoiding a lot of complex theory  • We are going to have a strategical battle @@StartBracket@@most Sicilian players are very gifted tactical players@@EndBracket@@    • We are going to be better prepared than our opponent @@StartBracket@@most of the players are focusing on Open Sicilians, not on Anti-Sicilians@@EndBracket@@    • We are still playing for an opening advantage, the Rossolimo is the main weapon of top players such as Fabiano Caruana, Magnus Carlsen, Levon Aronian, Anand Viswanathan, Michael Adams, and so on. }
3... g6 4. Bxc6
{ A move that has been popularized by the legendary Moldovian coach Viacheslav Chebanenko among his students: Viktor Bologan, Sergey Rublevsky, Viorel Iordachescu and others.   At first, it looks insane to give up the Bishop in such a way without being provoked by Black, but White is playing for a better pawn structure. Of course, over the years, chess has moved on from such dogma that a Bishop is always better than a Knight, 'whatever the weather'. }
4... bxc6
{ It's a riskier recapture strategically speaking because it creates an isolated pawn on  a7  , but on the other hand, it gives Black some dynamic assets, such as having a central pawn on the d-file, that will advance sooner or later. Black usually has two main plans:  • To play it slow with: Bg7-d6-Nh6-f6-Nf7-O-O and say that the Bishop Pair is a strong asset when the position is going to open up  • To play for a quick  5.--  ...d5  , trying to not give White an easy game }
5. d4
{ I decided to recommend this move for the surprise value, plus I think it's an underrated line and people will play it a lot more in the future. White's play is fairly simple and effective, while in the other lines the play was generally double-edged.  The point is that if Black plays the normal  5...cxd4  , we are going to reply by going  6.Qxd4  and ask a bunch of awkward questions. Black can try to keep our King in the center by going 5...Ba6!?, but as you will see White has enough resources to fight for an early edge. }
5... Bg7 6. dxc5
{ Taking the pawn, inviting Black to develop the Queen if he wants it back. }
6... Qa5+ 7. Nbd2 { Preparing to castle. } 7... Qxc5
{ Black's best option, but not the most played move! } 8. O-O
{ Rushing to castle, and play for a quick e5. } 8... Nf6 { Runs into e5. } 9.
Nb3 { Attacking the Queen. } 9... Qh5 10. e5
{ Attacking the Knight because Black has not palyed d6 before going Nf6. }
10... Ng4 11. Bf4 { Defending the e5 pawn } 11... Nxe5
{ Would drop the Knight. } 12. Nxe5 { Taking the Knight. } 12... Bxe5 13. Qxh5
{ This strong intermezo is the point! } 13... gxh5 14. Bxe5
{ White is up a Knight. } *

