{ Defending a2, by attacking the Rook. } 25... Ra7 26. c4
{ Defending the c pawn, and fixing the weakness on b6. } 26... g5
{ Is the only move to make White's life harder. } 27. h4
{ We have to sacrifice the pawn to get our Bishop back in business. } 27...
gxh4 28. a4
{ White has pressure on the Queen-side because the b6 pawn is fixed on a darq square, which means that it's going to be an easy target for the Bishop. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Rossolimo 3...g6 and 4...bxc6"]
[Black "Rossolimo 7...Qxc5 #24"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ Going for the Rossolimo! I've decided to pick this opening because it's giving us the following advantages:    • We are avoiding a lot of complex theory  • We are going to have a strategical battle @@StartBracket@@most Sicilian players are very gifted tactical players@@EndBracket@@    • We are going to be better prepared than our opponent @@StartBracket@@most of the players are focusing on Open Sicilians, not on Anti-Sicilians@@EndBracket@@    • We are still playing for an opening advantage, the Rossolimo is the main weapon of top players such as Fabiano Caruana, Magnus Carlsen, Levon Aronian, Anand Viswanathan, Michael Adams, and so on. }
3... g6 4. Bxc6
{ A move that has been popularized by the legendary Moldovian coach Viacheslav Chebanenko among his students: Viktor Bologan, Sergey Rublevsky, Viorel Iordachescu and others.   At first, it looks insane to give up the Bishop in such a way without being provoked by Black, but White is playing for a better pawn structure. Of course, over the years, chess has moved on from such dogma that a Bishop is always better than a Knight, 'whatever the weather'. }
4... bxc6
{ It's a riskier recapture strategically speaking because it creates an isolated pawn on  a7  , but on the other hand, it gives Black some dynamic assets, such as having a central pawn on the d-file, that will advance sooner or later. Black usually has two main plans:  • To play it slow with: Bg7-d6-Nh6-f6-Nf7-O-O and say that the Bishop Pair is a strong asset when the position is going to open up  • To play for a quick  5.--  ...d5  , trying to not give White an easy game }
5. d4
{ I decided to recommend this move for the surprise value, plus I think it's an underrated line and people will play it a lot more in the future. White's play is fairly simple and effective, while in the other lines the play was generally double-edged.  The point is that if Black plays the normal  5...cxd4  , we are going to reply by going  6.Qxd4  and ask a bunch of awkward questions. Black can try to keep our King in the center by going 5...Ba6!?, but as you will see White has enough resources to fight for an early edge. }
5... Bg7 6. dxc5
{ Taking the pawn, inviting Black to develop the Queen if he wants it back. }
6... Qa5+ 7. Nbd2 { Preparing to castle. } 7... Qxc5
{ Black's best option, but not the most played move! } 8. O-O
{ Rushing to castle, and play for a quick e5. } 8... d6
{ Preparing to develop the Knight. } 9. Re1 { Preparing to play e5. } 9... Nf6
10. Nb3 { Attacking the Queen, and preparing to break with e5. } 10... Qb6 11.
e5
{ Attacking the Knight and threatening to play exd6 if Black moves the Knight. So Black is forced to take, and create a weak isolated pawn on c6. }
11... dxe5 12. Nxe5 { Recapturing the pawn, and preparing Qf3. } 12... O-O 13.
Qf3 { Going for the Achilles' heel! The pawn on c6 is weak. } 13... Bb7 14. Qe3
{ Trying to stop Black from pushing c5, and open up the b7 Bishop. } 14... c5
{ It's an intuitive pawn sacrifice to activate the Bishops, and play for long term compensation. }
15. Qxc5 { We need to accept the challenge. } 15... Rfc8 16. Qxb6
{ Going for a pawn up endgame. } 16... axb6 17. c3
{ Limiting the g7 Bishop, and the c8 Rook. } 17... Nd5 18. f4
{ Supporting the Knight and controlling the e5 square. } 18... f6
{ Black has to open it up for the Bishops. } 19. Nf3 e5 20. fxe5
{ Creating an isolated pawn on the e-file for Black. } 20... fxe5 21. Ng5
{ White is a pawn up and will bring the Knight to e4. Black has some compensation with the Bishop Pair, but I think White's chances are better with the extra pawn and easier play. Black still has to prove for the compensation. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Rossolimo, 3...g6 and 4...dxc6 Part I"]
[Black "Rossolimo 7.Nc3 O-O #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ Going for the Rossolimo! I've decided to pick this opening because it's giving us the following advantages:    • We are avoiding a lot of complex theory  • We are going to have a strategical battle @@StartBracket@@most Sicilian players are very gifted tactical players@@EndBracket@@    • We are going to be better prepared than our opponent @@StartBracket@@most of the players are focusing on Open Sicilians, not on Anti-Sicilians@@EndBracket@@    • We are still playing for an opening advantage, the Rossolimo is the main weapon of top players such as Fabiano Caruana, Magnus Carlsen, Levon Aronian, Anand Viswanathan, Michael Adams, and so on. }
3... g6 4. Bxc6
{ A move that has been popularized by the legendary Moldovian coach Viacheslav Chebanenko among his students: Viktor Bologan, Sergey Rublevsky, Viorel Iordachescu and others.  At first, it looks insane to give up the Bishop in such a way without being provoked by Black, but White is playing for a better pawn structure. Of course, over the years, chess has moved on from such dogma that a Bishop is always better than a Knight, 'whatever the weather'.  Giving up the Bishop Pair early on in the game, but on the other hand, we are spoiling Black's pawn structure. Now Black has two recaptures available, both of them leading to highly theoretical debates nowadays.  The move 4...dxc6 is by far the most popular recapture, leading to a maneuvering game, with a stable pawn structure, while the  4...bxc6  recapture is riskier and can lead to some very original positions.   Recapturing from the side is the favorite way to play for agressive players, or in must-win situations with Black because the play can get very sharp, unlike 4...dxc6. The general issue for Black in capturing from the side though is that the light-squared Bishop is struggling to find a good place. }
4... dxc6
{ The main move, leading to a positional struggle. Let's talk about the position for a bit. So, you can see that Black has the doubled c-pawns, but as compensation Black has the Bishop Pair.   If you saw my recommendation against 2...g6, you know that the Bishop Pair is great, and it is, but this position is a little more complex than that. First of all, the position is semi-closed, so that makes it tough for the Bishops; second of all, Black is usually going e5 to step in the center, after which the dark-squared Bishop becomes a little passive.   It is not a tragedy for Black because White's main plan is to break with f4, which Black always replies by playing exf4.   We know by now that White's main plan is to play for f4 but, if Black goes for the quick 6...b6 line, the plan with a3-b4 becomes viable. Generally, I don't like the a3-b4 plan based on the Wang Hao-Carlsen game because Black gets a lot of dynamic play, but against 6...b6 you can go for it. }
5. d3 Bg7 6. h3 Nf6 7. Nc3 O-O
{ It was considered to be pretty solid, but i think i found a nice and simple plan to get an edge. }
8. Be3 { Developing the Bishop, attacking the c5 pawn. } 8... b6 9. a4
{ Threatening to play a5 to undermine the c5 pawn, and activate our Rook. }
9... e5 { Is ignoring White's idea. } 10. a5 { Threatening to take on b6. }
10... Rb8 11. axb6 { Activating the Rook. } 11... axb6 12. O-O
{ White has a typical Rossolimo edge, and can follow up with Qd2-Bh6, Ne2, Nh2, and the thematic f4 lever. }
*

