{ Going for the Rossolimo! I've decided to pick this opening because it's giving us the following advantages:    • We are avoiding a lot of complex theory  • We are going to have a strategical battle @@StartBracket@@most Sicilian players are very gifted tactical players@@EndBracket@@    • We are going to be better prepared than our opponent @@StartBracket@@most of the players are focusing on Open Sicilians, not on Anti-Sicilians@@EndBracket@@    • We are still playing for an opening advantage, the Rossolimo is the main weapon of top players such as Fabiano Caruana, Magnus Carlsen, Levon Aronian, Anand Viswanathan, Michael Adams, and so on. }
3... g6 4. Bxc6
{ A move that has been popularized by the legendary Moldovian coach Viacheslav Chebanenko among his students: Viktor Bologan, Sergey Rublevsky, Viorel Iordachescu and others.  At first, it looks insane to give up the Bishop in such a way without being provoked by Black, but White is playing for a better pawn structure. Of course, over the years, chess has moved on from such dogma that a Bishop is always better than a Knight, 'whatever the weather'.  Giving up the Bishop Pair early on in the game, but on the other hand, we are spoiling Black's pawn structure. Now Black has two recaptures available, both of them leading to highly theoretical debates nowadays.  The move 4...dxc6 is by far the most popular recapture, leading to a maneuvering game, with a stable pawn structure, while the  4...bxc6  recapture is riskier and can lead to some very original positions.   Recapturing from the side is the favorite way to play for agressive players, or in must-win situations with Black because the play can get very sharp, unlike 4...dxc6. The general issue for Black in capturing from the side though is that the light-squared Bishop is struggling to find a good place. }
4... dxc6
{ The main move, leading to a positional struggle. Let's talk about the position for a bit. So, you can see that Black has the doubled c-pawns, but as compensation Black has the Bishop Pair.   If you saw my recommendation against 2...g6, you know that the Bishop Pair is great, and it is, but this position is a little more complex than that. First of all, the position is semi-closed, so that makes it tough for the Bishops; second of all, Black is usually going e5 to step in the center, after which the dark-squared Bishop becomes a little passive.   It is not a tragedy for Black because White's main plan is to break with f4, which Black always replies by playing exf4.   We know by now that White's main plan is to play for f4 but, if Black goes for the quick 6...b6 line, the plan with a3-b4 becomes viable. Generally, I don't like the a3-b4 plan based on the Wang Hao-Carlsen game because Black gets a lot of dynamic play, but against 6...b6 you can go for it. }
5. d3 Bg7 6. h3 Nf6 7. Nc3 Nd7 8. Be3 e5 9. Qd2 { Threatening to play Bh6. }
9... h6 { Stopping White from playing Bh6. } 10. O-O b6
{ The modern way of handling this line, implemented by Magnus Carlsen. Black is defending the b6 pawn so he can maneuver the Knight to f8-e6-d4. Here I recommend going for the Nh2-f4, since the a3-b4 plan has been refuted by Carlsen in his game against Wang Hao. Black simply ignored White's play on the Queen-side and went Nf8-Ne6 and sacrificed a pawn on the Queen-side to gain the initiative with f5. }
11. Nh2 { We are sticking with the standard plan of going Nh2 and f4. } 11...
Nf8 { The Knight starts its journey to d4. } 12. f4
{ Threatening to take on e5. } 12... exf4 13. Bxf4
{ We always take on f4 with the Bishop in my repertoire! Rxf4 is playable, but you don't get additional options to play for e5-Ne4 as we do when we capture with the Bishop. }
13... Ne6
{ By far the best move, because it's forcing us to play Be3 otherwise Black gets a good position after Qg5! }
14. Be3
{ We prefer to go Bg3 in general to have e5 ideas, but here we need to avoid Qg5. }
14... Nd4 15. Rae1
{ The most aggressive, and the best continuation in my opinion! White is playing for e5 and Ne4 ideas. }
15... Be6 { Preparing to go long castle. } 16. e5 { Threatening to play Ne4. }
16... Nf5 17. Bf2
{ The only square for the Bishop, because Bf4 was running into g5. } 17... Qc7
{ The best square for the Queen, attacking e5. } 18. Nf3
{ Defending e5, preparing to play Ne4. } 18... O-O-O 19. Ne4
{ Centralizing the Knight, preparing to play b4. } 19... h5 20. a3
{ White has free play on the Queen-side. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@29@@EndBracket@@ Nasuta,G @@StartBracket@@2516@@EndBracket@@-Sethuraman,S @@StartBracket@@2624@@EndBracket@@ Karlsruhe 2019 }
*

