{ Black is trying to predict that we are going to play Be3, and have the c5 pawn protected.Once we go for Be3, Black's idea is to play e5 and put the Knight on e7, following up with a quick f5.This plan can be quite dangerous if it catches you off-guard. What you need to know is that this plan fails to the classical expansion on the Queen-side with a3-b4.Note that this is the only line in this repertoire where i recommend the a3-b4 plan! }
7. O-O { Getting our King to safety. } 7... e5
{ Is the point of this move order, otherwise we are transposing to other lines. }
8. a3 { Threatening to break with b4. } 8... a5
{ Is the standard reaction by Black to stop White from having a free hand on the Queen-side. }
9. Be3 { White is preparing to play Nbd2-Nc4 and then break with b4. } 9... Ne7
10. Nbd2 { Developing the Knight, heading to c4. } 10... Ba6
{ Stopping White from playing Nc4, but we can rotate to another typical idea for this a3-b4 plan. }
11. Qb1
{ A thematic place for the Queen in the a3-b3 plan.Normally, you don't want to make such moves with your Queen, but here White is obviously threatening to break with b4 next, and undermine the enemy Queen-side. }
11... f5 { Would be a big mistake because: } 12. Ng5
{ We can invade the enemy camp with the Knight. } *

