{ The standard move, connected with Nh6, Black is preparing to play Nf7. } 8.
a5 { Gaining space on the Queen-side, and threatening to play Be3! } 8... Rb8
{ Forced so Black can answer Be3 with b6. } 9. O-O
{ Getting our King to safety. } 9... Nf7 10. Be3
{ Developing the Bishop, attacking the c5 pawn. } 10... b6 11. axb6
{ Taking the pawn, activating our Rook. } 11... axb6 12. Ra7
{ Invading on the seventh rank. } 12... O-O 13. Nbd2
{ Developing the Knight, heading to c4. } 13... e5 14. Nc4
{ Activating the Knight. } 14... Be6 15. b3
{ We always want to recapture on c4 with the b pawn, if possible! } 15... Re8
16. Qa1 { Preparing to triple! } 16... Re7 17. Qa3
{ Preparing to bring the f1 Rook in the fight for the a file! } 17... Reb7 18.
Ra1 Qc7 { Black can only wait and try to defend. } 19. Rxb7
{ Trading a pair of Rooks, so we can invade with the Queen. } 19... Qxb7 20.
Qa7
{ White has a typical Rossolimo edge with a small but steady pressure along the a file.The simple threat of trading the Queens and playing Ra6 to attack the b6 pawn is very effective. }
