{ This line is recommended by Christof Sielecki in his Sveshnikov Course.It is similar with the 5...Qc7 but a little bit worse since Black lost flexibility with the dark squared Bishop. }
7. O-O e5 8. a3 { Works well here because Black is behind in development! }
8... Nf6
{ Black's best place for the Knight, implemented by Magnus Carlsen once against the main expert from the White side, Fabiano Caruana. }
9. Be3 { Following Fabiano's footsteps is the way to go! } 9... c4
{ Has been played by Magnus, getting rid of the doubled pawns in a tactical way. }
10. Nc3 cxd3 11. Qxd3
{ I like Fabiano's approach of playing a symmetrical, but more pleasant position: }
11... O-O 12. Rfd1 Be6 { Would allow White to go: } 13. Ng5 Rfe8 14. Nxe6 Rxe6
15. Qc4 Ne8 16. a4 { White's pieces are more active. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Rossolimo, 3...g6 and 4...dxc6 Part II"]
[Black "Rossolimo 6.h3 Qc7 #13"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ Going for the Rossolimo!I've decided to pick this opening because it's giving us the following advantages:  -we are avoiding a lot of complex theory  -we are going to have a strategical battle @@StartBracket@@the most sicilian players are very gifted tactical players@@EndBracket@@  -we are going to be better prepared than our opponent @@StartBracket@@most of the players are focusing on the Open Sicilians, not on Anti-Sicilians@@EndBracket@@  -we are still playing for an opening advantage, the Rossolimo is the main weapon of top players such as:Fabiano Caruana, Magnus Carlsen, Levon Aronian, Anand Viswanathan, Michael Adams, and so on. }
3... g6 4. Bxc6
{ A move that has been popularized by the legendary Moldovian coach Viacheslav Chebanenko among his students: Viktor Bologan, Sergey Rublevsky, Viorel Iordachescu and others.  At first, it looks insane to give up the Bishop in such a way without being provoked by Black, but White is playing for a better pawn structure. Of course, over the years, chess has moved on from such dogma that a Bishop is always better than a Knight, 'whatever the weather'.  Giving up the Bishop Pair early on in the game, but on the other hand, we are spoiling Black's pawn structure. Now Black has two recaptures available, both of them leading to highly theoretical debates nowadays.  The move 4...dxc6 is by far the most popular recapture, leading to a maneuvering game, with a stable pawn structure, while the  4...bxc6  recapture is riskier and can lead to some very original positions.   Recapturing from the side is the favorite way to play for agressive players, or in must-win situations with Black because the play can get very sharp, unlike 4...dxc6. The general issue for Black in capturing from the side though is that the light-squared Bishop is struggling to find a good place. }
4... dxc6
{ The main move, leading to a positional struggle. Let's talk about the position for a bit. So, you can see that Black has the doubled c-pawns, but as compensation Black has the Bishop Pair.   If you saw my recommendation against 2...g6, you know that the Bishop Pair is great, and it is, but this position is a little more complex than that. First of all, the position is semi-closed, so that makes it tough for the Bishops; second of all, Black is usually going e5 to step in the center, after which the dark-squared Bishop becomes a little passive.   It is not a tragedy for Black because White's main plan is to break with f4, which Black always replies by playing exf4.   We know by now that White's main plan is to play for f4 but, if Black goes for the quick 6...b6 line, the plan with a3-b4 becomes viable. Generally, I don't like the a3-b4 plan based on the Wang Hao-Carlsen game because Black gets a lot of dynamic play, but against 6...b6 you can go for it. }
5. d3 Bg7 6. h3 Qc7
{ This line is recommended by Christof Sielecki in his Sveshnikov Course.It is similar with the 5...Qc7 but a little bit worse since Black lost flexibility with the dark squared Bishop. }
7. O-O e5 8. a3 { Works well here because Black is behind in development! }
8... Nf6
{ Black's best place for the Knight, implemented by Magnus Carlsen once against the main expert from the White side, Fabiano Caruana. }
9. Be3 { Following Fabiano's footsteps is the way to go! } 9... c4
{ Has been played by Magnus, getting rid of the doubled pawns in a tactical way. }
10. Nc3 cxd3 11. Qxd3
{ I like Fabiano's approach of playing a symmetrical, but more pleasant position: }
11... O-O 12. Rfd1 Re8 13. Bc5 Bf8 14. Bxf8 Kxf8 15. Rd2 Be6
{ So far we have been following the game Caruana-Carlsen 2019, 16.Rad1 was played and then Fabi sacrificed his Queen for two Rooks, but i think that Fabiano's play could be improved: }
16. Qe3 { Threatening to land on the King-side. } 16... Kg7 17. a4 h6 18. Rad1
{ White is controlling the only open file. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10. Rossolimo, 3...e6 4.Bxc6"]
[Black "Rossolimo 4.Bxc6 dxc6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ Going for the Rossolimo! I've decided to pick this opening because it's giving us the following advantages:    • We are avoiding a lot of complex theory  • We are going to have a strategical battle @@StartBracket@@most Sicilian players are very gifted tactical players@@EndBracket@@    • We are going to be better prepared than our opponent @@StartBracket@@most of the players are focusing on Open Sicilians, not on Anti-Sicilians@@EndBracket@@    • We are still playing for an opening advantage, the Rossolimo is the main weapon of top players such as Fabiano Caruana, Magnus Carlsen, Levon Aronian, Anand Viswanathan, Michael Adams, and so on. }
3... e6
{ A very dynamical line! We can draw this conclusion by looking at the main ambassadors of this line: the Magician from Riga Alexei Shirov, and El Niño from Baku Teimour Radjabov, both known for their hyper-aggressive playing style. I think this line reached its peak in 2012 when Boris Gelfand used it 3 times in his World Championship match against Vishy Anand. From that point on the line has not been repeated in a World Championship Match, but it's still played quite often at all levels.   Black prepares to bring his King's Knight to e7 and then to put the question to White's Bishop, with the move ...a7-a6. In this case, the exchange on c6 will be favourable for Black, because he will recapture with the Knight and keep a healthy pawn structure. }
4. Bxc6
{ This is the move which Viacheslav Andreevich Chebanenko used to recommend to his pupils. Nothing is attacking the Bishop on b5, but nevertheless, White voluntarily exchanges it for the Knight. Now a very interesting position arises, with Black having doubled pawns. In addition, in this structure, he will not find it easy to activate his Bishop on c8. }
4... dxc6
{ It's a worse version compared to 3...g6 and 4...dxc6 because the Bishop on c8 is locked. }
5. O-O Nf6 6. Re1 Be7 7. d3 h6 8. e5 Nd5 9. Nbd2 a5 10. Ne4
{ White played Nfd2 and Qh5 with play on the King-side in the game: 1-0 @@StartBracket@@34@@EndBracket@@ Fedoseev,V @@StartBracket@@2674@@EndBracket@@ -Korobkov,P @@StartBracket@@2423@@EndBracket@@ Jurmala 2015 }
*

