{ A very dynamical line! We can draw this conclusion by looking at the main ambassadors of this line: the Magician from Riga Alexei Shirov, and El Niño from Baku Teimour Radjabov, both known for their hyper-aggressive playing style. I think this line reached its peak in 2012 when Boris Gelfand used it 3 times in his World Championship match against Vishy Anand. From that point on the line has not been repeated in a World Championship Match, but it's still played quite often at all levels.   Black prepares to bring his King's Knight to e7 and then to put the question to White's Bishop, with the move ...a7-a6. In this case, the exchange on c6 will be favourable for Black, because he will recapture with the Knight and keep a healthy pawn structure. }
4. Bxc6
{ This is the move which Viacheslav Andreevich Chebanenko used to recommend to his pupils. Nothing is attacking the Bishop on b5, but nevertheless, White voluntarily exchanges it for the Knight. Now a very interesting position arises, with Black having doubled pawns. In addition, in this structure, he will not find it easy to activate his Bishop on c8. }
4... bxc6 5. d3
{ I decided to pick this line over  5.b3  that was played in the match for the World Crown in 2012 between Anand and Gelfand. The point of  5.d3  is that we are solidifying the e4 pawn, and we are staying flexible with the Bishop. You will see that in some positions it makes sense to go for b3-Bb2. }
5... Ne7 { The old main line. } 6. Qe2
{ They teach you to develop the Queen last, so what is wrong with me that I am even adding an ''!'' to this move?! Well, here is the thing: the general rule is correct, and it applies in most of the cases, but unlike maths, chess is a sport, not a science. 6.Qe2 is a multi-purpose move, preparing to play e5 in some positions taking control over the dark squares, but most important, is that White stays flexible and is waiting for Black to commit, so for example once Black goes for Ng6, we are immediately pushing the h pawn down the board! }
6... Ng6
{ We have to pay attention now because Black is threatening to play  7...e5!  and then d6, to activate the c8 Bishop! }
7. h4
{ This should be the first thing that pops out to your mind when you see a Knight on g6! Most of the times you will force Black to play h5 and weaken the g5 square, or if he doesn't react, you can kick that Knight with h5, and put him in an awkward situation. }
7... h5 8. e5
{ ''Removing peg by peg!'' A Romanian saying meaning that we are combating fire with fire! Black was threatening to play e5, and open up the c8 Bishop, so actually 8.e5! is a prophylactical move directed against the light-squared Bishop. }
8... Be7 9. Qe4
{ Centralizing the Queen, stopping any f6 ideas to break the center. } 9... c4
{ Black is trying to confuse us, but the sacrifice is not impressive. } 10.
dxc4 Rb8 11. b3 Bb7 12. Nbd2 d5 13. exd6
{ This is very thematic in our preparation. We want to split their pawns and our Rook is not in danger, we can always play Rb1 if neccesary. }
13... Bf6 14. Rb1 c5 15. Qe3 Qxd6 16. Ne4
{ Forcing Black to concede the Bishop Pair. } 16... Bxe4 17. Qxe4 Bc3+ 18. Ke2
{ White's King was safe on e2, and with a pawn up went on to win in the game: 1-0 @@StartBracket@@30@@EndBracket@@ Popov,V @@StartBracket@@2557@@EndBracket@@-Alekseenko,K @@StartBracket@@2447@@EndBracket@@ St Petersburg 2013 }
*

