7... h5 8. e5
{ ''Removing peg by peg!'' A Romanian saying meaning that we are combating fire with fire! Black was threatening to play e5, and open up the c8 Bishop, so actually 8.e5! is a prophylactical move directed against the light-squared Bishop. }
8... f6
{ Black is trying to challenge our center, but now you can see better why h4-h5 was a good inclusion for White: }
9. Qe4
{ We know that the Knight is not defended on g6, now Black has to make an awkward move to defend the Knight. }
9... Kf7 { A sad necessity, but the lesser evil. } 10. Na3
{ It is better to go via this route to c4, because if you go for the other route @@StartBracket@@Nd2-Nc4@@EndBracket@@ the c1 Bishop will be closed for one move. In our case, it might not make a huge difference, but in other scenarios, the small details are making the difference. }
10... d5 11. exd6
{ The Key move behind our strategy! Now Black has to deal with doubled isolated pawns on the c file. }
11... Qxd6 12. Nc4 { Attacking the Queen. } 12... Qd5 13. Ne3
{ Offering a Queen trade in our terms! If Black wants to get rid of the Queens, he has to remain with the ugly pawn structure! }
13... Qxe4 14. dxe4
{ Let's analyze this endgame, because the strategy is important in this type of positions. White is better with a lot of moves, but the overall strategy is important to maximize your chances to convert. At first glance it looks like a symmetrical position, Black has the doubled isolated pawns, but on the other hand he has the Bishop Pair so you may think that the situation is pretty balanced.   Now that we dive a little bit deeper in the position, we can notice that the Bishop Pair is not an important factor here since the f8 Bishop is restricted by its own pawns, and also the c8 Bishop is lacking a useful diagonal. Now that we clarified that the Bishop Pair is not an asset in this position, we see that Black is left with the double isolated pawns on the c file. As a long term plan for White, the Bishop will be nicely placed on a3, from where it attacks the c5 pawn. The King will castle Queen-side, and the f3 Knight will be maneuvered to c4 via d2. }
14... e5
{ We will keep this move as the Main Line because it was played by the Magician from Riga, Alexei Shirov. }
15. g3 { A solid positional move, not allowing any Nf4 jumps. } 15... Be6 16.
Nd2 Ne7 17. b3 Nc8 18. Bb2
{ Topalov, V. @@StartBracket@@2739@@EndBracket@@ - Shirov, A. @@StartBracket@@2715@@EndBracket@@ Monte Carlo, 2002. 39 moves @@StartBracket@@½ -½ @@EndBracket@@. }
