1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ Going for the Rossolimo! I've decided to pick this opening because it's giving us the following advantages:    • We avoid a lot of complex theory    • We are going to have a strategical battle @@StartBracket@@most Sicilian players are very gifted tactical players!@@EndBracket@@    • We are going to be better prepared than our opponent @@StartBracket@@most of the players are focusing on the Open Sicilians, not on Anti-Sicilians.@@EndBracket@@    • We are still playing for an opening advantage, the Rossolimo is the main weapon of top players such as Fabiano Caruana, Magnus Carlsen, Levon Aronian, Anand Viswanathan, Michael Adams, and so on. }
3... Qb6
{ Is pretty similar to 3...Qc7, but the difference is that this move is attacking the Bishop on b5. }
4. Nc3
{ Developing the Knight, defending the Bishop, and threating Nd5 sometimes. }
4... e6 5. Bxc6
{ Forcing Black to recapture with the Queen if he wants to justify the previous play, and then we can start attacking it! }
5... bxc6 6. O-O { Getting our King to safety. } 6... d5 7. d3
{ Defending e4, keeping a solid pawn structure. } 7... Nf6 8. Na4
{ Attacking the Queen. } 8... Qc7 9. b3 { White is threatening to play c4. }
9... dxe4 10. dxe4 { Recapturing the pawn. } 10... Nxe4 11. Re1
{ Attacking the Knight. } 11... Nf6 12. Bb2
{ White has huge compensation for the sacrificed pawn, and will win the c5 pawn soon. }
