1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ Going for the Rossolimo! I've decided to pick this opening because it's giving us the following advantages:    • We avoid a lot of complex theory    • We are going to have a strategical battle @@StartBracket@@most Sicilian players are very gifted tactical players!@@EndBracket@@    • We are going to be better prepared than our opponent @@StartBracket@@most of the players are focusing on the Open Sicilians, not on Anti-Sicilians.@@EndBracket@@    • We are still playing for an opening advantage, the Rossolimo is the main weapon of top players such as Fabiano Caruana, Magnus Carlsen, Levon Aronian, Anand Viswanathan, Michael Adams, and so on. }
3... Nd4
{ Should not be underestimated! This move is obviously inferior to the mainlines, but still it requires a good reaction by White for an edge. This line reminds me of the Bird Variation of the Ruy Lopez, but I think it's an inferior version here since Black still has to make another move, in order to develop the f8 Bishop. }
4. Nxd4 { Creating doubled pawns for Black. } 4... cxd4 5. c3
{ This is accurate! Forcing Black to show his hand. } 5... dxc3 6. Nxc3
{ Recapturing the pawn, developing the Knight. } 6... g6 7. d4
{ Creating a strong pawn center. } 7... Bg7 8. O-O
{ Getting our King to safety. } 8... a6 9. Bc4 { Retrating the Bishop. } 9...
e6 10. e5 { Threatening Ne4. } 10... d5 11. exd6
{ We take the pawn and we threat to advance the d-pawn. } 11... Qxd6 12. d5
{ Is opening everything up. } *

