1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ Going for the Rossolimo! I've decided to pick this opening because it's giving us the following advantages:    • We avoid a lot of complex theory    • We are going to have a strategical battle @@StartBracket@@most Sicilian players are very gifted tactical players!@@EndBracket@@    • We are going to be better prepared than our opponent @@StartBracket@@most of the players are focusing on the Open Sicilians, not on Anti-Sicilians.@@EndBracket@@    • We are still playing for an opening advantage, the Rossolimo is the main weapon of top players such as Fabiano Caruana, Magnus Carlsen, Levon Aronian, Anand Viswanathan, Michael Adams, and so on. }
3... Na5
{ A rare move, the idea of which is to move the Knight away from the threatened ex­change on c6, and then, by attacking the Bishop on b5, regain the lost tempi }
4. c3
{ Making a square for the Bishop on c2, and getting a Ruy Lopez kind of position. }
4... a6 5. Ba4 { Preparing Bc2. } 5... b5 6. Bc2
{ Defending e4, preparing d4. } 6... Bb7 7. d4
{ Creating a strong pawn center. } 7... cxd4 8. cxd4
{ Keeping the strong center. } 8... Rc8 9. O-O { Getting our King to safety. }
9... Nf6 10. Nbd2
{ Preparing the standard Ruy Lopez route for the Knight: Nbd2-Nf1-Ng3. } 10...
d5 { Seems to be a little bit too early for this. } 11. e5
{ Attacking the Knight and leaving the c3-square ready for our Knight. } 11...
Ne4 12. e6
{ A typical positional sacrifice, directed against the f8 Bishop that will remain passive for a while. }
12... f6 13. Re1
{ White is much better because Black can't develop the King-side. } *

