6. Re1 { Defending e4. } 6... d5 7. e5 { Attacking the Knight. } 7... Nd7 8. d4
{ We have reached a very favorable ver­sion of the French Defense for White: he has seized space, successfully positioned his pieces and solidly defended the key pawn on d4. Note that in such a structure, the Black Queen would be better placed on b6, from where it exerts pressure on the d4 pawn, on c7, it does not have any particular prospects. }
