{ Going for the Rossolimo! I've decided to pick this opening because it's giving us the following advantages:    • We avoid a lot of complex theory    • We are going to have a strategical battle @@StartBracket@@most Sicilian players are very gifted tactical players!@@EndBracket@@    • We are going to be better prepared than our opponent @@StartBracket@@most of the players are focusing on the Open Sicilians, not on Anti-Sicilians.@@EndBracket@@    • We are still playing for an opening advantage, the Rossolimo is the main weapon of top players such as Fabiano Caruana, Magnus Carlsen, Levon Aronian, Anand Viswanathan, Michael Adams, and so on. }
3... Qc7
{ A normal move, the idea of which is to prevent the doubling of the pawns on c6. }
4. O-O { Getting our King to safety. } 4... a6 5. Bxc6 { Taking the Knight. }
5... Qxc6 6. d4
{ Opening the position because we have a development advantage. } 6... cxd4 7.
Nxd4 { Attacking the Queen. } 7... Qc7 8. Nc3
{ Developing the Knight, threatening Nd5. } 8... e6 9. Re1
{ Developing the Rook, preparing to sacrifice the Knight with Nd5. } 9... d6
10. Bf4
{ White's idea is to use his advantage in de­velopment to attack the pawn on d6 and force  the  Hedgehog structure d6-e6 to commit itself prematurely. }
10... e5
{ Looks tempting to fork White, but is it going to be enough to balance the game? }
11. Nd5
{ And the answer is: No! Because White has a strong initiative in the center. }
11... Qd8 12. Be3 { Preparing to recapture on d4 with the B. } 12... exd4
{ Wins the piece for now, but compensation is on its way due to White's lead in development. }
13. Bxd4 { The threat of going Bb6 is too strong. } 13... Be6 14. Bb6
{ Attacking the Queen, and preparing Nc7. } 14... Qc8 15. Nc7+
{ Forking the King and the Rook. } 15... Ke7 16. e5
{ Threatening to mate on d6, and opening up the position. } 16... dxe5 17. Rxe5
{ White is down a piece at the moment, but he is fully developed and ready to mate the enemy King. }
