[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15. Model Games"]
[Black "Banzea, A.B. vs. Polyakov, F. Porto Carras, 2018"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ I decided to include this game because I have a nice story about it. I was playing in the World Championship U18 in Porto Carras and I remember that this game was played the day after the free day @@StartBracket@@normally at this type of events, there is a free day in the middle of the tournament so that the players can rest for the important rounds@@EndBracket@@. I knew my opponent was usually allowing the Rossolimo, but my home preparation was to play with 5.O-O as I did before, and I had at least one game in the database that my opponent would have a look on. The funny story is that this line had very few games at that time, and I've never seen it at the top level, but I was also following the games played by the Romanian players at that event. I noticed a girl U10 playing this line with White getting a winning position, so I was puzzled by it –it looked very interesting! Of course the girl was prepared by a strong Grand Master, that's why it brought my attention to the line. I had a quick look at it on my laptop and found out that there were already a few GM games with it, so I have done some quick research to see what's what. }
1... c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. Bxc6 bxc6 5. d4
{ Getting back to the story, here I am actually playing the line! I was not really expecting to play it soon, I just had a quick look on it so that maybe I will use it at some point, but only a few days after I discovered it, I had it on the board! What I really liked about this line is that is very easy to understand, has a lot of traps, and it's not obvious what Black should do. The lines with 5.O-O are objectively also good for White, but deeply analyzed and very tough to understand! Honestly speaking, I always struggled against this particular line with 4...bxc6 but after I started playing with 5.d4 I wish I could have it in every White game! }
5... Bg7 6. dxc5 Qa5+ 7. Nbd2 Ba6
{ At first, it looks very promising for Black to keep White's King in the center, but White has a surprising way to take the initiative, as showed in the theory chapter. }
8. Rb1 { Inviting Black to take a poisoned pawn. } 8... Qxa2 9. b4 Bb5
{ This move was bad but the whole line is dubious for Black. } 10. Rb3 Nf6 11.
Ra3 Qe6 12. c4 { I knew Black is losing something. } 12... Nxe4 13. Qe2
{ 13.Re3  Maybe would have been better, but what I played was also quite practical, I think.  13...Nc3  14.Qc2  Ba4  15.Qd3  Qf5  16.Bb2+-  Picking up the Knight soon. }
13... Bc3 14. Rxc3 { Getting rid of the tricks! } 14... Nxc3 15. Qxe6 dxe6 16.
Bb2
{ The final point! Black is totally lost now.   16.cxb5??  Na2  17.Bb2  f6  18.bxc6  Nxb4∞  Black might be even playing for a win here. }
16... Ba4 17. Bxc3 { The pawns are very strong. } 17... O-O 18. Ke2 Rfd8 19.
Ra1 Bc2 20. Nd4 Bd3+ 21. Ke3 Bf5 22. Ne4 Bxe4 23. Kxe4 Rdc8 24. Ra6 g5 25. Nxc6
f5+ 26. Ke5 { Showing the power of an active King! } 26... Kf7 27. Nd4 Rd8 28.
Nxe6 Rd3 29. Nxg5+ Kg7 30. Bd4
{ And Black resigned in this position. Also another funny story, I met my opponent at the hotel after the tournament and he told me that during the free day he prepared all day to play the Sveshnikov Sicilian @@StartBracket@@because I had a few games whit the Open Sicilian@@EndBracket@@ and found a lot of great ideas for Black. You can also win against the Sveshnikov, but I think this game is a very good illustration of what happens if you bring your opponent into your territory and you can easily outplay him because you know the structure better. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15. Model Games"]
[Black "Caruana, F. vs. Kuznetsov, V. Ol'ginka, 2011."]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ I decided to pick this game because it's played by an emblematic player of the Rossolimo and it's a brilliant illustration of how effective the a3-b4 plan could be if Black allows White to go for it. }
1... c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. d3 Bg7 6. h3 b6 7. O-O e5 8. Be3
{ 8.a3!  Is more accurate as I showed in the theory chapter of this course, but at that time the Rossolimo was considered to be a Sideline! }
8... Ne7 9. Nbd2 O-O 10. Nc4 f6 11. a3
{ The concept is good, but Black had a surprising tactical maneuver that he missed.   11.a4!  Is another powerful plan in this structure, the point being:  11...a5  12.b4±  Would have been even stronger because Black has no way to avoid it! }
11... a5
{ Black tries to not give White a free hand on the Queen-Side but it only made things worse for him:   11...Nd5!  Would have been an improvement on Black's play!  12.Bd2  Nc7  The Knight is much better placed on c7 because it's controlling the a6 square after the opening of the a file, and also has ideas of Ne6-d4 or Nb5-d4.  13.b4  cxb4  14.axb4  Be6  15.Be3  Qd7∞  The ideal Ra3 would not work that well here due to Nb5!   11...Be6  Would not change much:  12.b4  cxb4  13.axb4  Qd7  14.Ra3±  The typical Queen-Side pressure with Qa1 next. }
12. b4
{ White delivers this break with his pieces on the ideal squares! The problem with this set-up is that it does not always work because if Black plays a better opening, this would run into a quick f5 as in the game between Wang Hao - Magnus Carlsen showed in the theory chapter of this course. }
12... axb4 13. axb4 Rxa1 14. Qxa1 b5 15. Ncd2 cxb4
{ White is down a pawn at the moment, but he is going to win it back with a much better position! }
16. Qa2+ { Forcing the King in the corner. } 16... Kh8 17. Bc5
{ Pinning Black and preparing to regain the pawn. } 17... g5 18. Ra1
{ Activating the Rook. } 18... Bd7 19. Qa5
{ A strong practical move! If Black goes for the endgame, White's active Rook is going to decide the game: }
19... Qe8
{ Black tries to keep the Queens on, but it's not going to improve his situation.   19...Qxa5  20.Rxa5  Rf7  21.Ra8+  Nc8  22.Bxb4+-  The Rook is just too active, the game could continue:  22...Kg8  23.Nb3  Bf8  24.Bxf8  Kxf8  25.Na5  25...Ke7   25...c5  26.Nb7+-  Winning the c5 pawn.  26.Nxc6+  Bxc6  27.Rxc8+-  White has a technical win. }
20. Qxb4 Rf7 21. Ra7
{ The activity of White's pieces is going to decide the game! } 21... Bf8 22.
d4 { Finally breaking the center is going to force Black's collapse. } 22...
Nc8 23. Ra8 exd4 24. Nb3
{ 24.Bxf8  Rxf8  25.e5+-  At this point everything wins. } 24... g4
{ Black tries something, but with all of his pieces on the last rank, it's not going to bother White too much. }
25. hxg4 Bxg4 26. Nfxd4 Bh6 27. Nf5 Bxf5 28. exf5 Rd7 29. Bd4 Kg8 30. Nc5 Rd5
31. Qb3 Bf8 { 31...Qe1+  32.Kh2+-  White will just win soon. } 32. Qg3+ Kf7 33.
Qc7+ Qe7 34. Rxc8 { Black resigned because Rxf8 was coming. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15. Model Games"]
[Black "Erdos, V. vs. Gledura, B. Zalakaros, 2014."]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3
{ I decided to pick this game because it has been played by some of the most promising Hungarian players of all time! With the White pieces we have Erdos Viktor, one of the biggest opening experts. His style is a beautiful mixture between fine positional play and sharp tactical complications when needed. I had the pleasure to meet him at the Romanian Superleague when he was playing on board 1 for my team. He is a very friendly guy and we had a very good atmosphere throughout the whole event leading to an honorable 4th place for our team, Viktor having the best performance on board 1, and I had the best performance on board 5. With the Black pieces we have a very young Benjamin Gledura, a well established 2650 GM nowadays studying in the United States. He is known for his entertaining chess and his victory over the Former World Champion Vishy Anand in Gibraltar 2016. }
1... g6 2. e4
{ The 'interesting' mark might seem quite odd here because it's a normal move, but the point of it is that Viktor is mainly playing closed games @@StartBracket@@1.c4/1.Nf3/1.d4@@EndBracket@@. The fact that he decided to go for   2.e4  here, transposing to something that he almost never plays. I think it's a good sign that the line is interesting for White at least. }
2... c5 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4
{ Finally we are transposing to our 1.e4 Repertoire! } 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6.
Qa4 { Preparing to play e5 next. } 6... d6 7. e5 { Exploiting the pin. } 7...
dxe5 8. Nxe5 Bd7 { The main move in this position. } 9. Nxd7
{ The point of the line, winning the Bishop Pair and playing for a small but stable edge. }
9... Qxd7 10. Be3
{ The accurate move order, preparing to play for a quick Rd1! } 10... Bg7 11.
Rd1 Qg4 { 11...Qc8  Is the main move I covered in great depth in the course. }
12. Rd4
{ Avoiding the immediate Queen trade, this is an alterntive to 12.Qb3.   12.Qb3  Is more accurate and the main move of the course, but the game is still very interesting. }
12... Qc8 13. Bb5
{ Preparing to give up the Bishop Pair for a better pawn structure! } 13... a6
{ 13...O-O  14.Bxc6  bxc6+=  Would have been more stubborn to keep the Queens on the board. Of course it's easy to say that after you know what happened in the game. }
14. Bxc6+ Qxc6 15. Qxc6+ bxc6
{ Now that the position has stabilized is time to take a deep breath and try to assess it. When we are evaluating a position, the first factor that comes to mind is King's safety. Here the situation is pretty even because without the Queens nobody is really in the danger of getting mated. The second factor would be piece activity, where we can see that again, there is not a huge difference, but White's Rook on d4 is ready to create some threats so we can safely say that White is slightly more active. Now here's the catch:   What are the weaknesses? It is at this moment where White's position stands out because Black has two isolated pawns on the Queen-Side @@StartBracket@@a6 and c6@@EndBracket@@ while White has two healthy pawn islands. Due to these factors White has a solid advantage in this endgame, and what he did next is very instructive: }
16. Ke2
{ A very strong and instructive move! White displays great understanding of this endgame! The King becomes very important in the endgame, so White does not need to castle. }
16... O-O 17. Rhd1 { Bringing the last piece into the game. } 17... e6 18. Rc4
{ Attacking the weakness. } 18... Nd5 19. Bd4
{ Another strong move! Trading Black's strong Bishop and keeping a healthy pawn structure! }
19... Rfc8
{ 19...Bxd4  20.Rdxd4±  Is the right recapture because if Black wants to trade the Knights, White will be able to recapture with the Rook on c3 and keep a healthy pawn structure! }
20. Bxg7 Kxg7 21. Rc5 { Fixing the weakness on c6! } 21... Rab8 22. b3 Kf8 23.
Rd4 { Activating the Rook. } 23... Ke7 24. Kd2
{ Notice how White is using his King to defend the Knight so he can attack the a6 pawn with his Rooks! This would have not been possible if White would have castled! }
24... h5 25. Ra5 Nxc3 { 25...Ra8  26.Na4+-  Was winning for White anyway. } 26.
Kxc3
{ The King plays a massive role on the Queen-Side! At the beginner level this position might seem very dry, but at GM level this is close to resignable! The fact that White's King is much more active combined with the Queen-Side pressure makes it impossible for Black to react: }
26... Rb6 27. Kc4 f6 28. f4 { Fixing the pawns. } 28... Rd8 29. Rxd8 Kxd8 30.
Kc5 Kc7 31. c4 { Black will run out of moves soon. } 31... h4 32. b4 e5
{ Black had to do something because he was getting into Zugzwang soon. } 33.
fxe5 fxe5 34. Ra3 { The Rook is going to collect the enemy pawns. } 34... Rb8
35. Rxa6 Re8 36. Rxc6+
{ Now I think it's pretty clear that White is winning. It is still instructive to see how White took care of Black's counterplay: }
36... Kb7 37. Rd6
{ 37.Rxg6  e4  38.Rf6  e3  39.Rf1  e2  40.Re1+-  Yes, it was also winning but why to allow the pawn to get to the second rank? }
37... e4 38. Rd7+ Kc8 39. Rd2 { Going to eliminate the last possible danger. }
39... e3 40. Re2 Re4 41. h3 Kd7 42. Kd5 Rf4 43. Rxe3 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15. Model Games"]
[Black "Harikrishna, P. vs. Navara, D. Prague, 2018."]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ I decided to pick this game because first of all is played by the inventor of our system, Pentala Harikrishna, and on the other hand i think it's a very instructive game for a Maroczy Bind structure, showing how venomous White's set-up is.The game itself is by no means a perfect game, also due to the rapid time control, but i think that what i am about to show you is going to improve your positional understanding of this type of position tremendously and help you use it in your own games. }
1... c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 { The start of the Hungarian Variation. }
4... Nf6
{ Playing against the 5.Bb5 system, but it does not really affect us in any way since we are continuing with our plan of going Be2, 0-0, h3, Qe3, Rd1.   4...Nc6  5.Bb5  Some people are afraid of this system, that's why they don't go for the most natural move 4...Nc6. }
5. Be2 Nc6 6. Qe3 Bg4
{ The idea behind this move is to give up the Bishop for the Knight having in mind that White will go for a Maroczy Bind, therefore it would be beneficial for Black to trade a pair of pieces due to the lack of space in his camp. This strategy makes sense for Black, but we will happily take the Bishop Pair.   6...g6  Is the main move. }
7. O-O g6 8. Rd1 Bxf3 9. Bxf3 Bg7 10. c4
{ Harikrishna generally likes to play with c4 when allowed.The main problem with this is as i said in the theory chapter, if Black starts with 3...Nf6 White will have to play 4.Nc3 and then there will be no c4 fun whatsoever.Very few people are playing that move order, but it won't be professional to base a repertoire on something that Black can avoid with a move order trick!Nevertheless White's set-up is still venomous even without c4!   10.c3  Playing with c3 also makes sense to limit the Bishop, as showed in the theory Chapter. }
10... Qc7 11. Nc3 Ne5 12. b3
{ Being a rapid game, White keeps it simple. In a longer time control game, I think Pentala would have considered to keep the Bishop further:   12.Be2!?  I think that somehow he missed the next move if Black takes the pawn:  12...Nxc4  13.Nb5!  Would have been a very strong intermezzo.  13...Qc8  14.Qc3±  White will win back the pawn with a better position. }
12... Nxf3+ 13. Qxf3 O-O 14. Be3 Qa5 15. Rac1
{ White has a comfortable position. } 15... a6 16. Bd2 Rfc8 17. h3 b5 18. Nd5
{ Hari goes for the natural move.   18.e5!  White could have speculated the fact that the enemy Queen is lacking squares!Of course, Hari would have found this in a classical game, but we are not going to focus on the small details too much.  18...dxe5  19.Na4  19...b4  20.Qb7  20...Rab8  21.Qxe7+-  White will win the Queen-Side pawns soon. }
18... Qd8 19. Be3
{ 19.Ba5!?  Could have been an interesting move, but in a rapid game it's tough to evaluate the following endgame:  19...Qxa5  20.Nxe7+  Kh8  21.Nxc8  Rxc8  22.Rxd6±  This could be very good for White, or Black can grab the initiative if you miscalculate something. The point is that it was a double-edged decision, so Hari goes for the simpler choice, not risking anything. }
19... Nxd5 20. cxd5
{ I wanted to come to this position because I think it's very instructive to see what happens. }
20... Rc3
{ David tries to stay active, but this is a very nice example of how difficult it is to play this seemingly 'dry' position as Black.   20...Bb2  This looks normal, but I think David was afraid to ever play b4. Strategically speaking it's very risky, as I showed in the following lines, but in the proper way it could have saved him.  21.Rb1  21...Bg7  22.Rdc1  Qa5!  This is the key move for Black to activate his Queen and hold the Queen-Side together.  23.Qe2  23...b4!  24.Rxc8+  Rxc8  25.Rc1  Rc3  26.Rxc3  Bxc3=  Here Black is fine because White is not in time to play with a4 and attack the Queen-Side pawns. From a human point of view, I think Black still has to be careful, but he is very active.   20...Qd7  Let's see what happens if Black goes for simplifications:  21.Qe2  Rxc1  22.Rxc1  Rc8  23.Rc2!  Fighting for the c-file!  23...Rc3   23...h5  If Black does nothing he can almost resign:  24.Qd1  Kh7  25.Qc1  Rxc2  26.Qxc2  Qd8=  Black can save the game in this miraculous way though.   26...Bh6  27.Qc6±  I think Black is already losing, practically speaking.  24.Rxc3  Bxc3  25.Qc2  25...b4  26.Qd3!  26...a5   26...Qc8  If Black has no active play and White can improve his position, he is simply lost.  27.Kf1  27...Kf8  28.Qc4!  28...Qxc4+  29.bxc4  a5  30.Ke2  a4  31.Kd3  Ke8  32.c5!  White will win a pawn soon.  32...dxc5  33.Bxc5  Be1  34.Kc4  b3  35.axb3  axb3  36.Kxb3+-  With a winning endgame for White due to the extra pawn.  27.a4+-  This brilliant move fixing the pawns is going to win the game for White.  27...Kf8  28.Qa6  Qc7  29.Bb6+-  White wins the Queen-Side. }
21. Rxc3 Bxc3 22. Rc1 Rc8
{ 22...b4  23.a4+=  Black is going to suffer a long time here. } 23. Qe2 Qa5
24. Rc2 Rc7
{ 24...b4  25.Qd1  Qb5  26.Bh6  Qb7  27.a4+=  Black is left with the bad pawns again.  27...bxa3??  28.Rxc3  Rxc3  29.Qd4+- }
25. Qd1 Be5
{ David cracks under pressure, and Pentala shows a nice understanding of the position:   25...b4  Would have kept Black in the game, but White is still pressing.  26.Qd3  f6  27.g4+=  White is controlling the board. }
26. Rc6
{ The c6 square is what really kills Black here. White is using the outpost in a great way. }
26... Rxc6 27. dxc6 b4
{ Too late.   27...Qc3  Would be resignable for Black after White plays:  28.Qc1+-  The passed pawn is too strong. }
28. f4 Bf6 29. Qe2 e6 30. Qd3 d5 31. exd5 exd5 32. Bd4 Bxd4+ 33. Qxd4 Qc7
{ David resigned because White was about to take the d5 pawn. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15. Model Games"]
[Black "Moiseenko, V. vs. Iljin, T. St. Petersburg, 2016."]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ I decided to pick this game because it is a technical masterpiece by a very experienced Grand Master. The first moves have been explained in the theory chapter of this course, so I am not going dive into that again, but I want you to focus on the Queen-less middlegame because I think it displays a very common scenario in the Rossolimo, where white has a positional advantage, and Black tries to sacrifice a pawn in order to activate his position and go for an active defense. }
1... c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 e6 4. Bxc6 bxc6 5. d3 Ne7 6. Qe2 Ng6 7. h4 h5 8. e5
f6 9. Qe4 Kf7 10. Na3 d5 11. exd6 Qxd6 12. Nc4 Qd5 13. Ne3 Qxe4 14. dxe4 Ba6
15. b3 e5 16. g3 c4
{ I think it was a good practical try, but Moiseenko shows crystal clear technique.   16...Be7  Would have been the passive alternative.  17.Nd2  Rhd8  18.Ndc4±  But Black clearly was afraid to play this position because his pieces are very passive, and he might lose the c5 pawn leaving White with a 3v2 majority on the Queen-Side. }
17. Nxc4
{ Forcing Black to give up the Bishop Pair.   17.bxc4?  Would have been good for Black because:  17...Bc5=  He will win back the pawn. }
17... Bxc4 18. bxc4
{ This is the position of interest. We have been following mainline theory that has been explained in the theory chapter of this course so far. I wanted to draw your attention to this kind of situation because in having the ugly pawn structure in the Rossolimo, Black is constantly going to look for opportunities to sacrifice a pawn in order to complicate matters. In the current situation, Black just sacrificed the pawn with c4 stating that this is going to give him better defensive chances instead of keeping the doubled pawn with a passive position.   I remember that when I was starting out in chess, I also thought that the doubled pawns should not be that big of a deal since they can't create a passer, which is a little bit of a misconception – and I will tell you why!   Let's look on the board: yes, White can't create a passer, but he can use the pawn to control additional squares! The pawn is not felt in terms of Queening, but it's increasing the activity of your pieces because you are controlling two extra squares compared to your opponent! Look carefully at this game because it is a beautiful conversion by White, showing the power of an extra @@StartBracket@@doubled@@EndBracket@@ pawn. }
18... Rb8 19. c3 { Stopping any Rb4 or Bb4 ideas! } 19... a5 20. Ke2 Bc5 21.
Rd1 { Activating the Rook. } 21... Nf8 22. Ne1
{ The Knight was not doing a lot anymore on f3, and now it's going to show it's full potential on d3! }
22... Ne6 23. Nd3 Rb7 24. Be3
{ 24.f4+-  Could have been even better than the game, but Vadim decides to keep it simple. }
24... Ba3
{ Black tries to keep more pieces on the board, but it gives White a crucial tempo:   24...Bxe3  25.Kxe3  Rd8  26.Rab1  26...Rbd7  Would have been more stubborn, but White is still better after:  27.Rd2+=  With an extra pawn. }
25. Rab1 Rhb8 26. Rxb7+
{ Giving Black the b file for the time being, because there is no way to use it! }
26... Rxb7 { All the squares from White's side are covered. } 27. Kd2 Bd6 28.
Kc2 g5 29. c5 Bc7 30. Nb2
{ Again, the Knight has a better square on c4! Notice how the doubled pawn is controlling the crucial b6 and d6 squares from Black's camp! }
30... gxh4 31. gxh4 Ke7 32. Nc4 a4 33. Nb6
{ Finally Black is forced to take the Knight, and the doubled pawn will become a strong passer! }
33... Bxb6 34. cxb6 c5 35. Rd5
{ 35.Rb1  Would have been more accurate, but what White did is still good enough.  35...Kd7  36.Kd3  Kc6  37.Kc4  Rxb6  38.Rg1!  It was tough to evaluate this position from far away because the a pawn look fast for Black:  38...Rb2  39.Rg6  Rxa2  40.Rxf6  40...Kd6  41.Bxc5+  41...Kd7  42.Be3  Nf4  43.Bxf4  exf4  44.Rxf4+-  But now it's pretty clear that the a pawn is not running anywhere. }
35... a3 36. Bc1 Rxb6 37. Bxa3 Ra6 38. Kb2 Rb6+ 39. Ka1 Rc6 40. Bc1
{ Preparing to push the a pawn, and also playing for f4. } 40... Nf8 41. f4
exf4 42. Bxf4 Re6 43. e5
{ White is opening the position because the difference between the Bishop and the Knight will start to tell! }
43... fxe5 { 43...f5  44.Bg5+  Kf7  45.Rxc5±  Was also tough for Black. } 44.
Bxe5 Ng6 45. Bg3 Re3 46. Rg5 Nf8 47. Bf2 Rxc3 48. Bxc5+ Kf7 49. Bxf8 Kxf8 50.
Rxh5 { The endgame is winning and Vadim shows no mercy. } 50... Ke7 51. Rb5 Rh3
52. h5 Rh2 53. a4 Kd6 54. a5 Kc6 55. Rf5 Kb7 56. Rc5 Ka6 57. Kb1 Kb7 58. Kc1
Ra2 59. Kd1 Rb2 60. Ke1 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15. Model Games"]
[Black "Oral, T. vs. Navara, D. LuhaÄovice, 2003."]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3 { The Westerinen Attack! } 3... d6 4. Bb2 Nf6
{ This is a very important line because you have to know how to play against Black's natural moves. Here the thing is that if Black manages to play Be7 and O-O without White achieving anything, then our set-up would not make that much sense. Fortunately for us, as pointed out in the theory chapter and in this game, White is showing a very dangerous way for Black to develop a King-Side initiative! }
5. e5
{ A concrete move, the point is that Black is more or less forced to take on e5 and then after the Knight captures on e5 White will be able to support it with f4! }
5... dxe5 6. Nxe5 Be7 7. Bd3 { The Bishops are already eyeing the King-Side. }
7... Nbd7 8. f4
{ The key move of our set-up! If Black could have got rid of the e5 Knight his position would have been easy to play. Now after Nxe5 it would be very tricky for Black to play after White plays the pawn recapture fxe5! }
8... O-O 9. O-O Re8 10. Na3
{ A common route for the Knight, heading to c4.   10.a4!?  Could be a small improvement as I showed in the theory chapter multiple times. }
10... Nb6
{ Black is trying to meet Nc4 with Nxc4, therefore White goes for another idea, leaving Black with an awkward Knight on b6. }
11. c4 Bd7 12. Rf3
{ Memorize this Rook lift because it is very important for this structure. Black will simply get outnumbered on the King-Side! }
12... Bf8 13. Rh3
{ Already creating the threat of Bxh7! Notice that Black is very close of getting mated in the first 15 moves! }
13... g6 { Had to be played in order to stop White from playing Bxh7. } 14. g4
{ White is threatening to play g5, getting rid of the main defending piece from Black's camp! }
14... Re7 15. g5 Ne8
{ Notice that White has 5 attackers against Black's lonely King, therefore the tactics should work in White's favor. }
16. Rxh7 Kxh7 17. Qh5+ { The Bishop and the Queen are cooperating nicely. }
17... Kg8 18. Nxg6 { Opening up the diagonal for the b2 Bishop. } 18... fxg6
19. Qh8+ Kf7 20. Qh7+ { White is going to pick up the g6 pawn. } 20... Bg7 21.
Bxg7 e5 22. Qxg6+ Kg8 23. Qh7+ Kf7 24. Bh6+ { With mate to follow. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15. Model Games"]
[Black "PredojeviÄ, B. vs. DraziÄ, S. Å½upanja, 2007."]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The game started as a French Defense, but it will transpose to our O'Kelly Sicilian soon.   1...c5  2.Nf3  a6  3.c3  e6  4.d4  d5  5.e5  Bd7  6.Bd3  cxd4  7.cxd4  Bb5  8.Bc2  Is our move order. }
2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Bd7 5. Nf3 a6 6. Bd3
{ Even though the game started as a French Defence, we are transposing to our O'Kelly Sicilian. }
6... cxd4 7. cxd4 Bb5
{ So this is the key position of the line. Black is trying to get rid of the French Bishop and justify the early a6 in this French Structure. }
8. Bc2
{ At first, it looks dangerous to avoid the trade because White will not be able to castle short, but in fact the h1 Rook can activate via h3 after playing h4! This idea is what I consider to be the refutation of Black's concept. The Bishop will be 'active' on b5, but that activity will be useless since White can just play around that diagonal. Also notice that the c2 Bishop, compared to his light-squared colleague on b5, is keeping an eye on the King-Side! }
8... Bb4+ 9. Bd2
{ 9.Nc3  Is the move that I recommend in the course, but White has more than one way to secure a solid advantage. Anyways, the type of position is the same regardless of the small details. The key move was 8.Bc2! because after that White has many ways to obtain a promising position. }
9... Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 a5 11. Nc3 Ba6 12. h4 Nc6 13. Qg5
{ Borki goes for a one sided endgame!   13.Rh3!?  Is another promising continuation keeping the Queens on the board. }
13... Qxg5
{ 13...g6  14.Qd2!  Now that Black weakened himself, the Queen journey is justified.  14...h5  15.Na4  15...b6  16.a3  Nge7  17.O-O-O  Bb5  18.Nc3  Bc4  19.Ng5±  White is ready to push g4. }
14. hxg5 { The key move putting a lot of pressure on h7! } 14... Nb4
{ 14...Nge7  15.Kd2!  Kf8  16.Rac1  g6  17.Na4±  The Knight is going to arrive on c5 soon. }
15. Kd2
{ What Borki does is very instructive, demonstrating the fact that the King is very strong in the center because there is no danger of getting mated!   15.Ba4+  Was more precise to keep the Bishop, but what Borki did also makes a lot of sense and is very instructive.  15...Kf8  16.Kd2!  Ne7  17.a3  17...Nbc6  18.Bxc6  Nxc6  19.Rac1±  White is going to play Na4-Nc5. }
15... Nxc2 16. Kxc2 Ne7 17. Kd2 Rc8 18. Rhc1
{ White decides to focus on the Queen-Side.   18.Rh3  Was another promising idea.  18...Kf8  19.Rah1  19...Kg8  20.Ne1!  A very instructive maneuver, allowing White to push the King-Side pawns.  20...Nf5  21.Nc2  21...g6  22.g4  22...Ne7  23.Na3  Kg7   23...Nc6  24.Nab5  Bxb5  25.Nxb5±  The Knight will land on d6.  24.f4±  White will play Na4-Nc5 while the h3 Rook can also join the Queen-Side initiative. }
18... Nc6 19. Na4 { The key maneuver heading to c5! } 19... Ke7 20. Rc3
{ White is preparing to double the Rooks. } 20... h6 21. gxh6 Rxh6 22. Nc5 Nb8
{ 22...Rg6  Would have been the lesser evil, but White has the better position.  23.g3  23...Rg4  24.Nxa6  bxa6  25.Rac1  25...Kd7  26.b3+=  White has a better pawn structure. }
23. Rac1 Rg6 { Now it's too late to activate. } 24. g3 Rc7 25. Nxa6 Rxc3 26.
Rxc3 Nxa6 27. Rb3 { Black is losing the b7 pawn, and with it the game. } 27...
Nb4 28. a3 Nc6 29. Rxb7+ Kd8
{ 29...Ke8  30.Rc7+-  White was picking up the a5 pawn. } 30. Rxf7 Kc8 31. Kc3
a4 32. Ne1 Rg4 33. Nc2 g5 34. Rg7 Kd8 35. Kd3 Kc8 36. Rh7 Kd8 37. Rh3
{ The Rook is trapped on g4. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15. Model Games"]
[Black "Short, N. D vs. Zhu, L.L. Devenport, 2014."]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This game has been played by the English Legend, former Candidate, Nigel Short. Even though the gap between the players was very significant, Nigel is showing crystal clear play in a Simultaneous Exhibition! }
1... c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3
{ The Westerinen Attack, one of the most underrated Anti-Sicilians! } 3... Nc6
4. Bb2 d6
{ This is a popular move for Black, trying to finish development with Nf6 without allowing White to push e5. }
5. d4
{ White is entering an Open Sicilian with a clear-cut plan: to play Nc3-Qd2-O-O-O and push g4 and checkmate the enemy King! }
5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 Nf6 7. Nc3 Be7 8. Qd2 O-O 9. O-O-O a6 10. Kb1
{ A very nice and useful move! Before starting the initiative on the King-Side, White makes sure there won't be any shenanigans with Bg5 or the a2 pawn would be hanging in some lines. }
10... Qc7 11. g4 Rd8
{ It's not losing material, but it's just very passive:   11...Nxg4?  Is only speeding up White's Attack:  12.Rg1!  12...Nf6  13.Rxg7+!!  The Bishop on b2 is making everything possible!  13...Kxg7  14.Nf5+!!  14...exf5   14...Kh8  15.Qh6  15...Rg8  16.Nd5!!  16...exd5  17.Bxf6+  And Black gets mated.  15.Nd5!  15...Qd8  16.Qg5+  Kh8  17.Nxe7+-  White is mating.   11...Nxd4  Would have been the best reaction, but White still has a lot of compensation:  12.Qxd4  e5!  13.Qd2  Bxg4  14.Re1  Rac8  15.Rg1=∞  Black has to be very careful on the g file. White can also push f4 next and try to trap the Bishop with f5. }
12. g5 Ne8 13. h4 Nxd4 14. Qxd4 b5 15. f4
{ White is increasing his lead in the center slowly but surely. } 15... Bb7 16.
Rh2
{ A beautiful move, avoiding any tricks on the a8-h1 diagonal and making the Rook a multi-purpose piece now, defending the Queen-Side while also attacking the enemy King! }
16... d5 17. e5 { Closing Black's Bishop on b7! } 17... Bc5 18. Qd3 g6
{ 18...d4  19.Ne4+-  The Knight is ready to land on f6 at any moment. } 19. h5
Ng7 20. hxg6 { Opening up the h-file for the attack. } 20... hxg6 21. Qh3 Nh5
22. Be2
{ White is simply getting rid of the annoying Knight and checkmate is unavoidable. }
22... Kg7 23. Bxh5 gxh5
{ 23...Rh8  Was maybe more stubborn, but White is completely winning anyways:  24.Qd3  Rxh5  25.Rxh5  gxh5  26.f5+-  With mate to follow soon. }
24. f5 Qd7 25. Qxh5 *

