1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6 4. O-O Bd7 5. Re1 Nf6 6. h3
{ Careful at the move order! This is very important to not allow Black to go for Bg4 lines!   6.c3  Is also very common, but Black has the option of:  6...a6  7.Bf1  Bg4∞  And is a completely different game compared to what we have looked on in the theory chapter. }
6... a6 7. Bf1 e5 8. c3 Be7 9. d4 Qc7 10. d5 Nd8 11. a4
{ A typical move to gain space on the Queen-Side! White is also threatening to fix the Queen-Side with a5 if Black is not careful. }
11... b6 { Stopping White's idea of going a5. } 12. Na3
{ A common way for White to develop the Knight, in some positions the Knight goes to c4, or White simply goes for Queen-Side play with b4. Nevertheless a useful move. }
12... O-O 13. Bd3 { Preventing an eventual Ne8-f5. } 13... Nb7 14. Nh2 Na5
{ Black is threatening to play c4 and create counterplay on the Queen-Side, so White's reaction comes in time: }
15. c4
{ Stopping any active ideas that Black had at his disposal before starting the King-Side play with f4! }
15... Rfe8 16. f4
{ Now that Black has no active possibilities, White can start an attack without being bothered! }
16... exf4 17. Bxf4 g6 18. Nf3
{ Bringing the Knight back in the game, looking to break with e5.   18.e5?  Nh5∓  Would have been much better for Black! }
18... Nh5 19. Bh2 Bf6
{ Stopping White from playing e5, but misplacing the Knight, therefore White goes: }
20. g4 Ng7 21. Qc2 { Developing the Queen, and defending the b2 pawn. } 21...
Qd8
{ Threatening to play h5 and weaken our King-Side, but Maxime has a cool reaction:   21...h5  Was not doing much now because of:  22.g5±  White is controlling the board. }
22. Re2 h5 23. Rg2 { Just in time with the defence. } 23... hxg4 24. hxg4 b5
{ Black tries to complicate the matters a little bit. } 25. Rf1
{ But the Queen-Side is so solid that White can just ignore it and focus on his King-Side play! }
25... bxc4 26. Nxc4 Nxc4 27. Bxc4 Qc8 28. e5
{ Maxime finds a beautiful combo, sacrificing material for the time being, but his pieces will increase their power significantly! }
28... dxe5 29. Nd2 Bg5 30. Ne4 Qd8 31. Qf2 f5 32. gxf5 Bh4 33. d6+ Be6 34. fxe6
{ Not needed, but Maxime gets extra points for style!   34.Qe2+-  Was also winning. }
34... Bxf2+ 35. Rfxf2 Qh4 { 35...Nxe6  36.Bxe5+-  The King gets mated. } 36.
e7+ Kh7 37. Nf6+ Kh6 38. Bf7 g5 39. Bg3 *

