1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ Going for the Nimzowitch Variation of the Sicilian! With the Black pieces, we have its main expert, GM Rakhmanov. This game is a perfect illustration of how White should be approaching this pawn structure, staying flexible, and improving his position little by little. }
3. e5 Nd5 4. Nc3 Nxc3 5. dxc3 Nc6 6. Bf4 Qb6
{ Black's trickiest plan, forcing White to make a big decision very early in the game. }
7. b3
{ The standard reaction, keeping options to castle long, and also not misplacing the Queen with a move such as Qc1. }
7... h6 8. h4
{ Taking space on the King-Side and stopping Black's idea of pushing g5. } 8...
e6 9. Qd2 Qc7 10. h5
{ Fixing the King-Side and not showing where White is going to castle yet. It's very important to stay flexible in this pawn structure. }
10... b6 11. Bd3 { The Bishop is going to e4. } 11... Bb7 12. Be4
{ 12.O-O-O  a6⇆  Black could try to attack our King if we rush with long castle. }
12... O-O-O 13. O-O-O
{ Now that Black showed his hand, we can safely castle Queen-Side. } 13... b5
14. Kb1 { Always useful after castling. } 14... Ne7 15. Qe2 Bxe4 16. Qxe4 Qc6
{ Black had nothing better than to go for a worse endgame. } 17. Qxc6+ Nxc6 18.
Nd2 { A strong maneuver, activating the Knight! } 18... Na5 19. Ne4 Nb7 20. g4
{ Gaining space on the King-Side. } 20... f6
{ Black tries to sacrifice a pawn to complicate the matters.   20...Kc7  If Black does nothing White will improve his position slowly:  21.Rh3  21...Kc6  22.Rhd3  Be7  23.f3+=  White can go a3-b4 next. Black is suffering with the backward pawn on d7. }
21. exf6 gxf6 22. Nxf6 { Calling the bluff! } 22... Bg7 23. g5
{ White goes for the most energetic continuation!   23.Ne4  Would have kept Black in the game:  23...d5  24.Ng3  Bxc3∞ }
23... Rhf8 { 23...hxg5  24.Bxg5±  White has a strong passer on h5! } 24. Bg3
{ A multi purpose move, defending the Knight on f6 and setting up a devilish tactic! }
24... hxg5
{ 24...Bxf6  25.gxf6  Rxf6  26.Bh4+-  Was one of the ideas behind Bg3. } 25.
Ne4 Bh6 26. Rd6
{ For sure what Rakhmanov missed, Black is just lost now after this brilliant idea! }
26... g4
{ 26...Nxd6  Would not be possible because:  27.Nxd6+  Kc7  28.Nf5+  d6  29.Nxh6+-  White wins material. }
27. Ra6 { Black has no way to defend his Queen-Side. } 27... Bf4 28. Bh4 Rde8
29. Nf6 Re7 30. Nd5 Rh7 31. Nxf4 Rxf4 32. Bg3 Rf5 33. Rxa7 e5 34. Ra8+ Kc7 35.
h6 Nd6 36. Rg8 Nf7 37. Rg6 Kb7 38. Rh4 Rg5 39. Rxg5 Nxg5 40. Rxg4 Ne6 41. Rg6
e4 42. Be5 { And Black resigned here because the exchange sac was looming: }
42... Kc6 43. Rxe6+ dxe6 44. Bg7 *

